INSERT INTO `letter` VALUES (1,'Sharuminyinka','I wanted to thank you again for your help. Speaking with you was energizing; I have started searching for Tig with renewed focus.\r\n\r\nI have a gift for you. And a story.\r\n\r\nOne place I have explored very little is the Sea of Dreams. It borders the World of the Dead - a dangerous place, even for gods and goddesses (I\'m sure you have heard the story of Persephone, and the pomegranate). I spent some time trying to receive an audience with Twtw, hoping to receive his blessing, but he would not see me. I was told he was \"unavailable\", though during one of my visits I saw Cú Chulainn leaving. I suppose the request of an all-but-forgotten goddess holds very little weight.\r\n\r\nAfter visiting every day for a full month, I gave up, but on my way out happened to meet a hery-heb priest of Twtw\'s named Akhentutu. He recognized my divinity, and asked about my errand. Apparently he had noticed my frequent visits. I told him that I was seeking a blessing before traveling the Sea of Dreams, and his excitement was apparent. He told me that a trip across the sea had been organized by Black Hactcin, and was departing in four days. Akhentutu was responsible for gathering many of the supplies needed for the trip, and he had been working with several of Black Hactcin\'s shamans. He offered to introduce me to one of them - a woman named Sonsee-array - whom he believed could get me passage aboard the ship.\r\n\r\nWe met at the docks that evening. Sonsee-array was a quiet woman, but powerful. I\'m not sure most mortals would have recognized it, but Akhentutu clearly did. He spoke to her with almost as much deference as he had with me. It seems he has a special sense - and respect - for the spark of divinity, in all its forms. I have no doubt he will become an excellent high priest for Twtw.\r\n\r\nSonsee-array took me to see Black Hactcin. To my surprise, he knew my name, though if he knew more he did not say. He allowed me passage, and assigned one of his other shamans to serve me: Goyathlay.\r\n\r\nGoyathlay is nothing like the great leader whose name he shares, but he is capable, knowledge enough, and I appreciate that he does not attempt to hide the fact that he\'s reporting our every activity to Black Hactcin. During the three days leading up our departure, Goyathlay escorted me around town, and helped me in my preparations for the journey. If Black Hactcin wants to know the foods I sampled, and the prayers I made, he may do so; I only hope he doesn\'t forget.\r\n\r\nIt\'s now the night before we depart. I\'ll write again. Until then, please enjoy my gift: some Feseekh I picked up at the market.\r\n','The Sea of Dreams',200,NULL,16,11),(2,'Sharuminyinka','I was thinking about those pets of yours. There\'s one you call a \"Desikh\". I should have asked about them while I was in Egypt. I suspect \"Desikh\" is just a name some human \"discoverer\" gave them, but even so, it\'s a peculiar choice, and certainly sounds Egyptian. I wonder what their creators called them? And whether those creators also created the portal that your city is based around, or if it\'s just a tear; a result of centuries of disrepair.\r\n\r\nA lot of things get forgotten to time. Maybe the true name of the Desikh has already been completely erased from history.\r\n\r\nI won\'t let that happen to Tig.\r\n\r\nWe\'ve been traveling the Sea of Dreams for a few days now; in that time, I\'ve learned quite a bit about it from Goyathlay: what lives beneath its surface, its various currents, wayfinding prayers, and the like. It\'s not difficult to guess my plan, and I\'m sure Gayathlay has reported it to Black Hactcin. They won\'t try to stop me, though. I\'m not threatening Black Hactcin\'s domain, and I don\'t think even a god such as he would risk breaking The Sunflower Laws.\r\n\r\nWe found a Zaratan this morning - or an Aspidochelone, as you may know it - and went ashore to enjoy the Coconuts and Kalpa tree fruits growing on it. We\'re to meet back on the ship this afternoon, but I won\'t be joining them.\r\n\r\nI noticed your people like to collect seashells. While exploring the back of the Zaratan, I found one. I hope you enjoy it.\r\n\r\nI\'ll write again.','Preparations',145,NULL,NULL,NULL),(3,'Katica','We - Katica, Pepca, Neli, and Aurora - leave these letters so that our story will not be forgotten. We go knowing that we will likely die, but also knowing that we will have revenge! Revenge for our fallen sisters! Revenge for our queen! Revenge against the white warrior-queen Porcelain, and her followers, who massacred our colony!\r\n\r\nWe four sisters are the sole survivors of that bloody day. The day Porcelain\'s betrayal was revealed.\r\n\r\nWe had long suspected that a thief was among us: food had been going missing for almost a month, and we even began to suspect that some of the eggs had been going missing. Additional guards were posted, but it was hard to believe that one of our own would betray us, and so we looked outward.\r\n\r\nNo one suspected Porcelain. She was weak. Small. Her wings broken. That she survived the metamorphoses into a pupa was a miracle. As an adult, not fit to be a queen, she was put to work. She could barely do even that job. In hindsight, her constant mistakes and failures were almost certainly a lie intended to throw us off her trail. While we worked for the colony, she stole from it. The food she stole from us - from our queen - was going to her, her secret hatchery, her secret army of mottled, mutant ants!\r\n\r\nOne day, after a storm, we were out collecting food from a fruit tree that had fallen nearby. We were going to have a feast that night, to celebrate the colony\'s good turn of luck. Almost everyone was out collecting. That\'s when Porcelain and her army attacked. They had built their own nest, around and intertwined with ours, with secret entrances connecting the two. They burst into every room and corridor at once. Several us were sent out to call back the workers who were gathering, but it was already too late. Our queen had been killed.\r\n\r\nSome would say that it was cowardice that made the four of us flee to the trees rather than stand and fight. Cowardice that we watched the battle from above; watched as our sisters were cut down; watched as Porcelain\'s army ransacked our home, and marched away, carrying our food and unborn sisters to feed themselves. But we are not cowards. We are warriors! And we will have revenge!','We Will Have Revenge',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(4,'Katica','We tried to follow Porcelain\'s army. They marched out of the woods we knew, and into grassy fields, with no signs of stopping. With no colony to support us, food was hard to come by, and we feared that the birds would take us. An ant without a colony is as good as dead. Four ants is not much better.\r\n\r\nPepca - a scout - had heard that the northern colonies had recently become embroiled in an ant-bee war that had been sweeping the country. She suggested we enlist. At first, we turned the idea down. As outsiders, we would never be truly accepted by another colony. But as days wore on, we were growing hungry, and weary. Neli\'s antenna broke when a gust of wind blew us off a rock. In tending to her wound, we fell behind, and almost lost Porcelain\'s trail entirely. Next time an accident happens, we might lose it for good. And so we agreed to Pepca\'s plan. By joining the war, not only would we be fed and cared for, we could train, visit many places, meet ants, and other creatures, and gain connections that could potentially lead us to Porcelain.\r\n\r\nThat evening, we found one of our queen\'s eggs, dropped by Porcelain\'s army. I can\'t say I didn\'t think of eating it - the thought crossed all our minds - but we buried it, set up camp, and ate some old snail slime we found nearby. At least it probably wasn\'t riddled with dicrocoelium dendriticum.\r\n\r\nTomorrow, we head north. I leave Neli\'s antenna with this letter. We have to move quickly if we\'re to make it to the northern colonies.','The Ant-Bee War',425,NULL,NULL,NULL),(5,'Hyssop','\\*k-chk\\*\r\n\r\n\\*ssssssss\\*\r\n\r\n**Muffled voices:** Hello? What are you doing? Testing it. Is it on? The light is blinking. It was blinking before! Wh-- no it wasn-- Give me that! \\*shkshkshk\\* Hey! \\*shkshk\\* You\'re gonna break it! \\*shkshkshk\\*\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** HELLO. My name is Hyssop.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** No fair!\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** And these are my *very best* friends, Honeybottom, and Thorn.\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Hi.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** ...\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** You can\'t just look at me and say *nothing*: it\'s a recording! *Nothing* doesn\'t get recorded!\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** I know that!\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Then why didn\'t you say anything? Human tools are clearly beyond you.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Hmph!\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Anyway. Where were we?\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Our brother.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Yes. But not our literal brother.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** I know that, too!\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** I was saying it for the human. But wait: wasn\'t it our sister?\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** I think-- wait... I forget, too.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** We should have done this earlier, then we\'d remember.\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** I do remember. It was our brother. Brother, uh...\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Ha! You don\'t remember the name!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Well. Perhaps we *should* have done this earlier...\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** You don\'t remember their name, but--\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** BUT: regardless: we wanted to thank you, human, for helping, uh, *them* escape from that wretched raccoon! As well as for helping--\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Are you sure it wasn\'t one of those awful magpies?\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** AS WELL AS--\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** I can guarantee that it was absolutely a raccoon.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** But you can\'t remember their name.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** \\*sigh\\*\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** I can: it\'s name was Tiffin.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Not the raccoon! Our... brethren!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** We already established that I don\'t remember our *brother\'s* name. The raccoon\'s name, however, I remember very well. Hyssop wouldn\'t stop repeating it.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** It *is* a funny name! Tiffin! *Tiffin!*\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Stop.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** \\*clears throat\\* Yes. As *I* was saying. To you, uh, *human*... of the physical realm. World. We extend our *deepest* gratitude! Your good deeds - not only in your world, but in ours - have not gone unnoticed! As it is very uncommon that one of your kind takes notice of us!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Very poetic. But to be fair, it was more the deeds of that pet of theirs.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** I was gonna say that!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Fortunately, we can *both* say it.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** But--\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** BUT: it doesn\'t matter: you don\'t credit Glitterwing Moths for lighting a path; you credit the fae who captured them, put them in lanterns, and hung them up.\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** What about the fae that feed them? I believe in the case of Glitterwing Lanterns, you\'d *actually* credit the kingdom who hired the various fae--\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** It was a bad example. The human was not employed by our kingdom to--\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** *But* the organization that built the encampment around the \"portal\"--\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** BUT: *it doesn\'t matter*, because *our* king and queen - Rambutan and Hollydew (may they be forever beautiful) -\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom & Thorn:** Forever beautiful.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Gave US the job of thanking THE HUMAN. *Not* their pet, and *not* their... weird human organizations!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Fair.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Ha!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** ...\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** What did I say about recording silence?\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** You told Honeybottom not to do it. But your point is taken. I\'ll be more careful in the future. Please continue.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Yes. Thank you. IN the name of Rambutan and Hollydew (may they be forever beautiful),\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom & Thorn:** Forever beautiful.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** We offer you our gratitude, and this gift: a Hyperchromatic Prism!\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Oh, Hyssop: you should probably tell them what a Hyperchromatic Prism is.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** What? Why? Do you want me to explain a Glitterwing Lantern, as well?\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** You already did that.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** \\*sigh\\*\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** I was just thinking that... just like I don\'t know what a human \"tape reekordur\" is, maybe *they* don\'t know what a fae Hyperchromatic Prism is.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Honeybottom! You\'re right. That\'s a very good thought.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Thank you! *One* of us has to be the sympathetic one!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** You mean \"empathetic\".\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** And one of us has to be a *thorn* in everyone\'s side!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** And your tongue must not be as sweet as your bottom, because it keeps uttering jokes as tired and old as you are.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Old?! TIRED!? That\'s no way to talk to your older brother!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** You mean older and *tireder* brother.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** \"TIREDER\"\'S NOT EVEN A WORD! YOU! YOU!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Hey!\r\n\r\n\\*clunk\\*\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Ah! Guys, stop! I almost--\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Let go of me!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** *You* let go of *me*.\r\n\r\n\\*scrape\\*\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Ah, sorry about that, human. I\'m just--\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** If you bite me, I will end you.\r\n\r\n\\*chk\\*\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Just gonna go outside now...\r\n\r\n\\*k-tunk\\*\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** \\*exhales\\* This is why I don\'t have siblings. *Actual* siblings, I mean, this time. They are very nice, though. Honeybottom and Thorn. I promise. Uh. I was saying something... the prism! Yes: the Hyperchromatic Prism! Well, so in case you don\'t already know, you just shine it on one of your pets, and that pet\'s coat will shimmer and shine, and change over time! (Ooh, that rhymed!) Uh, but mostly the change is pretty gradual, but it *can* jump around a bit, from time to time. Well: you\'ll see! Anyway, sorry, this recording went on a bit longer than expected. Hopefully it won\'t take the couriers long to bring it to you! Thanks again, and don\'t forget to keep that fireplace going!\r\n\r\n\\*chk\\*\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** We stopped fighting already.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Well, you\'re too late: I pressed stop already.\r\n\r\n\\*k-chk\\*','Fae-kind Thanks You',652,NULL,NULL,NULL),(6,'Hyssop','\\*k-chk\\*\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** --ood this time, right?\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** The light is blinking.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** What?\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** You already pressed \"record.\"\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Ah! Well. No time like... the past!\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom & Thorn:** ...\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** GREETINGS, HUMAN! Uh. Again! Your continued displays of kindness toward not only faekind, but to all the denizens of the Umbra, continue to impress us!\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** You said \"continue\" twice.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** The way you resolved the dispute between a burning treekin and hungry emberling, by finding a bit of charcoal for the emberling, once again demonstrates your uncommon sympathy-- I mean: empathy.\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Eh.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** See? It\'s hard!\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** \\*clears throat\\* ON BEHALF of king Rambutan and queen Hollydew (may they be forever beautiful),\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom & Thorn:** Forever beautiful.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** We once again extend our thanks, and offer you this gift: a bottle of Quinacridrone Magenta Dye, which we understand is something of a rarity in the physical world-- er: realm. World?\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Quinacridone.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Yes. That. And, uh... that\'s it! Short and sweet this time!\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Thank you!\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Yes! Thank you, again.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop & Honeybottom:** ...\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** Thanks.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Thank you. Er, to Thorn. But also to you, too, human. Again. I guess. Again-again.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom:** Shush and press \"stop\" already.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Fi--\r\n\r\n\\*k-chk\\*','Our Continued Thanks',455,NULL,NULL,NULL),(7,'Hyssop','\\*k-chk\\*\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** Greetings again, human! In appreciation of the *enduring flame* you have kept in your home, in the name of king Rambutan and queen Hollydew (may they be forever beautiful),\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom & Thorn:** Forever beautiful.\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** We thank you, and offer you this gift: a piece of Firestone, which we are able to forge thanks to your support.\r\n\r\n**Honeybottom & Thorn:** Thank you!\r\n\r\n\\*ssssssss\\*\r\n\r\n**Hyssop:** That was perfect, you guys!\r\n\r\n**Thorn:** You didn\'t press \"stop\".\r\n\r\n\\*k-chk\\*','We Are Brightened by Your Enduring Flame',136,NULL,NULL,NULL),(8,'Mia','Can you believe it\'s already been a year? (And what a year it\'s been!) I had hoped to visit everyone individually for their one-year anniversaries, but the number of people who arrived just within the first year was beyond our expectations and wildest dreams! It would take me a year just to say \"hello\" to all of you!\r\n\r\nThis town started as a research outpost, back in 2004. When we started, there were only eight people, but over the course of seven years, thanks to volunteers such as yourself, we grew to the thousands! Unfortunately, we later lost our head researchers, and with them, our funding, forcing us to close down most of our operations for a number of years. But a fortunate turn of events, and new sponsorship, has allowed us to resume operations, and we\'ve been delighted with the response!\r\n\r\nI know that I\'m new myself, having only joined in 2019, but allow me to welcome and thank you on behalf of everyone at Hollow Earth Research Group. Your enthusiasm and positivity motivates us every day! With your help, we know we can uncover the secrets of this island, its portal, and the strange (and cute) creatures that live there!\r\n\r\nThanks again for being a part of HERG!\r\n\r\nPlease enjoy this One-year Anniversary Gift. (And don\'t worry: I had one donated to the Museum on your behalf!)','Your One-year Anniversary',899,NULL,NULL,NULL),(9,'Sharuminyinka','I awoke this morning, but I\'m not sure how long it\'s been since I wrote you. I appear to have washed up on the shores of a small island, and cared for by... someone. I found my clothes drying outside the hut I was sleeping in. But though I spent the entire day searching, I found no other signs of intelligent life on the whole archipelago.\r\n\r\nI remember having so many dreams, but I\'ve already forgotten so much. I should have started writing the moment I woke up, but... well, it\'s hard to remain calm when awaking in an unfamiliar place.\r\n\r\nTranquil currents of thought lead to recondite eddies; warm undulations of fond, old memories sent me over underwater waterfalls, and into biting trenches and dark imagination. Were they memories, or just fictions created by a mind under stress? I\'m not sure.\r\n\r\nOne memory does stand out, however, and somehow feels more important than the others: an old man, or maybe woman - I can\'t remember what they looked like - but they smelled of vetiver and sage. They spoke of a traveler... a woman with a sword. They told me her name; it was something old, but I\'ve already forgotten the sounds. We\'re looking for the same thing, she and I, yet not the same thing.\r\n\r\nI think another dream had a dragon in it, but that could mean anything. There\'s a dragon for every star in the universe, plus the three.\r\n\r\nI\'ve wasted my time. This morning. Maybe this whole trip. There\'s so much I can\'t remember, but it\'s there, just below the surface of my memory; beneath the waves of the Sea of Dreams. I\'m watching them now... images lapping at the sands; swirling around rocks and pebbles. If I reach out for them, I\'ll only disturb them further.\r\n\r\nI have to get back. But before then, I have to rest, and regain my strength.\r\n\r\nMaybe my caretaker will show themself.','A Lonely Island',879,NULL,NULL,NULL),(10,'Sharuminyinka','I was on the islands for six days. Resting. Waiting. Thinking. Building, or trying to.\r\n\r\nI learned that I am certainly not a goddess of the sea: I cannot build a boat, raft, or anything seaworthy. I am quite good at destroying such vessels, however, so perhaps I could be one of those sea goddesses that takes the lives of sailors with dark storms, giant waves, and leviathans.\r\n\r\nDoesn\'t seem to fit, somehow.\r\n\r\nThis afternoon, while thinking about these things, I watched something approach: a small raft with an even smaller shelter on it, piloted by a young boy, although I suppose he would prefer to be referred to as a man.\r\n\r\nHe was certainly not my caretaker. His name is Tifkli, and while he seems capable for his age, he is no more wise for it. His naïveté - and quick infatuation with me - were plain to see. He is honest, at least, which is good, both because he doesn\'t have the experience to be a liar, and because I\'m feeling impatient after almost a week of failed shipwrightmanship.\r\n\r\nTifkli came from a village of islanders with an uncommon tradition: when their children \"come of age\" - at only years 15 - they leave their island in search of another. The first island they find, they settle, and the cycle continues.\r\n\r\nThe boy had expected to find a populated island, but admitted that the possibility of finding an uninhabited one was something he\'d prepared for. He says he\'ll wait years if he must, farming, fishing, and building. He assumed I had come to the island in the same way. When I explained my situation - or as much as I was comfortable - he was disappointed, of course, but remained logical. Again: he is not good at hiding his feelings, but it seems he\'s at least self-aware enough to realize when his feelings aren\'t serving him. I suppose a people who raise their children to travel alone across the ocean must prioritize a sort of survivalist logic, at least. He was even willing to give me his raft, after some discussion.\r\n\r\nI\'m on the open sea again, and I should feel better, but I don\'t. I feel like I\'ve freed myself of the islands, only to find myself a slave to the currents. And I don\'t like being this close to the water. I catch glimpses of it, even if I don\'t mean to, and images from my dreams come back. Some of them are interesting - mysteries I want and need to solve - but others are unsettling. None of them are fun, or relaxing. All require attention. Thought. Analysis. It\'s tiring. I spent centuries in Gizubi\'s gardens. Why can\'t I dream of those times?\r\n\r\nRereading my letter, I realize how dreadful I must sound. How depressed. I\'m just tired. I knew searching for Tig would be hard. I suppose that\'s why I wasted those centuries with Gizubi\'s court. But I\'m searching now. If nothing else, these dreams have given me new questions. I\'ll find my way out of here; I\'ll get answers; I\'ll find Tig.\r\n\r\nRemember us.','Remember Us',450,44,NULL,NULL);
