/*!40000 ALTER TABLE `monthly_story_adventure_step` DISABLE KEYS */;
INSERT INTO `monthly_story_adventure_step` VALUES (1,1,NULL,'Hunting','HuntAutoScaling',23,20,43.4,85,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(2,1,NULL,'Opportunity','Story',24,23,33,88.7,3,3,'We emerged from the woods at nightfall, high above the sea. Below us, a port town well-lit with torches and lanterns, and still bustling with activity.\n\nWe found a dark patch on one side of town, snuck in, and assumed the roles of pirates.\n\n---\n\nWe explored the taverns and shops for a couple hours, and simply listened. Many spoke in codes, but many more were loud, over-confident, and loose-lipped, especially when drinking.\n\nThe recent change in leadership among the various pirate groups was the topic of several conversations. The Unraveller, as we knew him, had taken the name Tishpak, after a god of war that was defeated in battle many years ago. He lived on a smaller island just off the west coast of Dragonhead Island. His ship had come to port just a couple days ago - apparently after some long adventure - and many were envious of the supposed parties and feasts taking place on Tishpak\'s island.\n\n---\n\nIt didn\'t take us long to find a small supply ship making runs for Tishpak. We silently disposed of its crew, dropping their bodies in the ocean, and set sail.','Ship',NULL),(3,1,NULL,'Rest','Gather',12,11,83.4,13.7,3,3,'Not wanting to stay in that ruined village, we traveled down the lake and found a place to set up camp, and rest.',NULL,NULL),(4,1,NULL,'','Story',17,16,76.6,57.7,3,3,'We headed south, towards Dragonhead Island.\n\nBased on what the keepers of the lighthouse had told us, that was where the largest band of pirates lived. That was where the Unraveller would be found.\n\n---\n\nWe knew we\'d have to cross the water to get there, but we had hoped it would be a shorter distance. Walking on ice would be more dangerous than solid ground, and we did not want to get caught on the open water.\n\nAfter some discussion, we agreed to risk the long \"walk\". We would begin as soon as the sun set, and hope to make it to the other side before sunrise.',NULL,NULL),(5,1,NULL,'Signs of Pirates','Gather',14,13,85.7,32.1,3,3,'While traveling down the coast, we found a semi-permanent encampment, currently uninhabited, but it seems pirates sometimes stop here.\n\nNot wanting to risk being spotted, we left to camp over a nearby hill... but not before taking one of their flags.','BlackFlag',NULL),(6,1,NULL,'Shaluria Bay','Story',1,NULL,5.5,53.4,3,3,'Our Lord sent a messenger to us last night, telling us to go to Shaluria Bay, a place once home to the Shalurian Empire. Before its fall, the Shalurians were said to be technologically and spiritually advanced; now it lies in ruin, and its land is occupied by those who do not find the laws of civilization to their liking. It is a place feared for its pirates, criminals, and wild beasts, but druids, nomads, and hermits also live there.\n\n---\n\nWe camped on a beach at the edge of Shaluria, discussing what reason our Lord might have for sending us here. It _is_ a place that reminds one of the decay of the universe, but it does not seem like a place important enough to warrant the attention of the gods.\n\nWhatever the reason, we will find it.\n\nWe enter Shaluria tomorrow.',NULL,NULL),(7,1,NULL,'Travel','Gather',2,1,16.3,57.6,3,3,'We crossed into Shaluria this morning. The only signs of human life we\'ve seen are the occasional ship at sea.\n\nAs we traveled, we collected and ate local herbs and vegetables.',NULL,NULL),(8,1,NULL,'Lost in the Woods II','Gather',9,8,49.5,14.4,3,3,'We wandered in a daze, following imagined voices...',NULL,NULL),(9,1,NULL,'Led Astray','Story',7,5,43.6,12.9,3,3,'Today we decided to leave the beach. It had begun to give us a feeling of vulnerability, and the woods nearby seemed to offer shade and shelter.\n\nBut at night, a darkness fell over the forest; a darkness beyond what was natural in the mortal world.\n\nThrough the darkness we heard voices, some pleasant, and some fearful. We followed the pleasant ones, and avoided the others, becoming lost without even becoming aware of it...',NULL,NULL),(10,1,NULL,'Fishing','HuntAutoScaling',15,14,85.9,43.9,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(11,1,NULL,'Lost in the Woods','WanderingMonster',8,7,49.9,4.3,3,3,'In the darkness, we were attacked by creatures which were unfamiliar to us...','TwilightChest',NULL),(12,1,NULL,'Lost in the Woods III','WanderingMonster',10,9,60.3,8.9,3,3,'In the darkness, we were attacked by creatures which were unfamiliar to us...','TwilightChest',NULL),(13,1,NULL,'Hiking Through the Hills','Gather',4,3,28.2,35.1,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(14,1,NULL,'Tracking','Gather',21,20,61,93.3,3,3,'As we traveled south, the tracks were getting more fresh, rather than older - we were catching up to someone!',NULL,NULL),(15,1,NULL,'Keepers of the Lighthouse','Story',5,4,36.1,22.6,3,3,'Traveling up the coast, we could see a great lighthouse in the distance - remains of the Shalurian Empire - somehow still in operation.\n\n---\n\nAs we approached the lighthouse, we saw a shanty town had been built up around its base, surrounded by crude walls.\n\nMen at one of the gates stopped us, but after a display of our power, we were allowed in, and escorted to the town\'s leaders: a small circle of men and women who represented the people of the town.\n\n---\n\nThey feared that we were pirates, sent from Dragonhead Island to make demands of them. After assuring them that we were not, they explained that they had come to an agreement with the various pirate bands in the area: to be left alone, unharassed, in exchange for maintaining the lighthouse, upon which all the pirates depended. This agreement had held for many years, but recently the keepers of the lighthouse had perceived a shift in power among the pirate bands - new uniforms, flags, and captains - and they were acting more aggressively; here was concern that the agreement might not be respected for much longer.\n\nA shift in the local power structure... could this be related to what our Lord had sent us here for?\n\n---\n\nWe stayed the night, learning about these keepers of the lighthouse of Shaluria, before parting ways the following morning.','ShalurianLighthouse',NULL),(16,1,NULL,'Signs of Struggle','Story',20,19,55.9,84.1,3,3,'As we approached the edge of the woods, it began to rain. Before we could reach the trees for shelter, however, we stumbled upon some dead bodies in the tall grass. A fight had taken place here not long ago.\n\nTracks lead west, towards pirate territory, but also south.\n\nThe rain started to pick up, so we ran for the treeline. While we waited for the rain to stop, we decided on our next move.\n\nThe storm passed before long, giving way to a clear sky, and enormous rainbow.','Rainbow',NULL),(17,1,NULL,'Hunting Boar','HuntAutoScaling',3,2,22.4,46,3,3,'It seems Shaluria Bay is home to a unique breed of boar. We hunted a couple before camping on the beach to rest.',NULL,NULL),(18,1,NULL,'Hunting Boar','HuntAutoScaling',13,12,89.4,22.5,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(19,1,NULL,'The Unraveller','Story',11,10,74.9,9.3,3,3,'Through some miracle, we escaped the forest. Had our Lord gave us strength, or had the darkness of the woods merely become bored of us?\n\nSeeking to get as far from the woods as possible, we fled across the fields that now lay before us, following an animal trail until it lead us to a ruined village that straddled a river.\n\nWe took shelter in the burned-out remains of a hut, and resolved to stay the night there.\n\n---\n\nAs the sun began to set, we saw a ship coming up the river. A pirate ship.\n\nIt stopped in the lake, and we watched a landing party approach the village shore. Its leader, a wild-looking Ruqu, barked commands at his inferiors. His impatience, and the fear of his men, could be felt from across the water.\n\nStill recovering from the woods, and sensing danger, we decided to hide, and watch.\n\n---\n\nThe captain\'s men took a prisoner was taken from one of the smaller boats, and threw him at the captain\'s feet. Their words could not be heard, but the nature of their conversation was clear: the prisoner\'s life was at risk, and the Ruqu captain wanted something of him.\n\nNight was starting to fall, and the crew began lighting torches. After gathering some supplies, the prisoner lead them through the village. We followed from a distance.\n\n---\n\nThe pirates stopped at a half-destroyed house. It was a large house surrounded by land; the house of a wealthy family.\n\nThe prisoner remained silent and motionless by the captain\'s side as pirates searched the house\'s remains.\n\nHalf an hour later, a woman emerged from the house. In her hands, a small, silvery box gleamed in the torchlight. She walked over to the captain, holding the box as though it were a ceremonial object.\n\nThe captain received it, and began to open it.\n\nSeeing a moment of opportunity, the prisoner ran, but the captain snapped the box shut, drew a sword, and threw it at the prisoner, impaling him. Rather than falling to the ground, the prisoner hung in the air, held up by a sword which refused to fall. The captain shouted something, then reeled his sword in on threads of Quintessence as the prisoner\'s bare feet flailed weakly at the sand, trying to resist.\n\nThis was the power of a Vassal. But it felt different. Though we had never been in the presence of such a being before, we all knew instinctively: this was not the Vassal of a god, but of the forces that were eating away at the fabric of the universe. This was an Unraveller.\n\n---\n\nKnowing we couldn\'t win in our current condition, we continued to hide our presence, and watched.\n\nThe captain unraveled the prisoner, absorbing what little Quintessence his mortal soul possessed, leaving nothing but gray ash and a pile of clothes. His crew watched in silent terror.\n\nAfter a moment, he ordered everyone back to the ship, and like being awoken from a spell, they jumped to life, and began packing up.\n\nThe Unraveller admired his box before tucking it into his cloak, and following his crew back to the lake\'s edge.\n\n---\n\nWe waited until long after they left - until we could see the pirate ship beginning to move out of the lake - before emerging from our hiding spot.\n\nOur purpose was clear now. _This_ was what our Lord had sent us here for. To destroy this Unraveller. We would not leave this place until that task was complete.',NULL,NULL),(20,1,NULL,'Ship Graveyard','TreasureHunt',16,15,78.1,54,3,3,'On the island were a number of wrecked ships. We camped in the remains of one, and found an old captain\'s log in one of the rooms. Many of the pages were damaged to the point of being unreadable, but among those we _could_ read were hints of a hidden treasure!','TreasureMap',NULL),(21,1,NULL,'Camping','HuntAutoScaling',18,17,73.8,79.2,3,3,'After a long night, we camped on the beach, catching fish for breakfast.\n\nWe took it in turns to keep watch, and slept without incident.',NULL,NULL),(22,1,NULL,'Words of Warning','Gather',19,18,65.2,81.3,3,3,'We ran into a small group of people who apparently live off the land and sea of the island. They told us a good place to gather berries, and warned us of a large pirate encampment to the west.\n\nWe thanked them for the information, and parted ways.',NULL,NULL),(23,1,117,'Tishpak','Story',25,24,15.4,87.6,3,3,'As we approached the Unraveller\'s island, we realized we didn\'t know exactly where to go. Fortunately, we found the ship\'s ledger, which included notes for deliveries to Tishpak; these were apparently among this ship\'s most important duties.\n\nThe dock was nestled in a crevice of the cliff which circled most of the island, lit by a minimum of torches, and largely obscured by foliage. The entrance was clearly intended to be a secret, known only to those Tishpak trusted.\n\nWe saw dockworkers and guards readying themselves for the delivery, and made a hasty plan: we jumped into the water, and allowed the boat to drift to the dock. The people on the dock began shouting when they realized the boat wasn\'t under human control, and it crashed into the dock.\n\nAs people rushed to the scene to see what was going on, we climbed up a darkened part of the dock, and slipped inside.\n\n---\n\nWe followed a path up the island, until we came to a castle. We could feel the Unraveller\'s presence from within: waves of divinity and wild chaos emanating from behind the castle\'s walls.\n\nWe climbed up to a window on the top floor, and entered into a darkened bedroom. It was empty. As was the hall outside. And the next room. And the next.\n\nNot a single person was seen. We thought they had been driven away by the Unraveller\'s oppressive aura... until we found him.\n\nTishpak the Unraveller was standing in a courtyard surrounded by piles of ashes and clothes. Next to him was the box he had taken from the ruined village, and in his hands was a stone, glowing with energy, pulsing. It wasn\'t the Unraveller\'s presence we had felt, but that of this stone.\n\n---\n\nTishpak hadn\'t seen us yet. His attention was fully on the stone. But for what purpose, and for how long, we didn\'t know.\n\nWe began a prayer to our Lord, and split up, taking different positions in the roof of the courtyard. Once in position, we drew our weapons, and made our attack.\n\nI leaped down, blade drawn, directly above Tishpak, aiming for his head. In a flash he tucked away the stone and drew his sword, but as our swords met, he realized his mistake. He began to turn around to face my companions, but they had already run him through from behind.\n\nWe spoke the final word of our prayer, and Tishpak collapsed, the Unraveller soul within him consumed by our Lord.\n\n---\n\nWe searched his body for the mysterious stone, but it could not be found. We expanded our search to courtyard, then to the castle, then to the entire island.\n\nNothing.\n\nIn his last moments, had the Unraveller sent the stone away? Destroyed it? Or worse: perhaps he had completed whatever ritual he had started, and the stone had been consumed?\n\nIt is clear the Unravellers act according to some plan, or laws of nature of their own, but other than a desire to end creation, those plans and laws remain a mystery to us, and to our Lord...','WrappedSword',NULL),(24,1,NULL,'Prisoners','RecruitTown',22,21,73.6,93.9,3,3,'The tracks lead to a quarry flying the pirate flag. They had slaves working in the pit, carrying out Stone, Marble, and other minerals.\n\nWe debated whether or not the Unraveller might be here - whether it would be safe to attack - and so watched the place for a while.\n\n---\n\nNight fell.\n\nHaving seen no signs of the Unraveller, we made our attack: we snuck into the encampment, and ambushed their barracks, finishing most of the pirates there without a fight.\n\nMost of the rest fled; the ones that didn\'t were easily defeated.\n\n---\n\nWe freed the slaves the pirates had captured. Most of them decided to take small boats back to the mainland; a few decided to stay on the island, and make a living there; one had been inspired by our divine presence, wished to join us, and our Lord saw fit to bestow them with immortality.',NULL,NULL),(25,1,NULL,'Ancient Ruins','TreasureHunt',6,5,18,23,3,3,'We explored the surrounding area, and found an old Shalurian site. It appeared undisturbed, so we decided to check it out.\n\nIn a building that appears to have been a storeroom, we found some supplies.','BoxOfOres',NULL),(26,2,NULL,'','MineGold',16,15,18.7,63.7,3,3,'We stopped to rest near a gold vein.',NULL,NULL),(27,2,NULL,'','CollectStone',18,17,39.7,83.4,3,3,NULL,NULL,'Left'),(28,2,NULL,'','CollectStone',19,18,29.8,89.4,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(29,2,NULL,'','Story',17,16,27.6,74.9,3,3,'We finally emerged from the narrow passage, into another cavern. Our fungal companion, without pausing, began walking to the east, but the three of us stopped. Beyond the forest of stalactites and stalagmites, we felt something. A font of magic energy.\n\nThe mushroom-person turned back toward us.\n\n\"Our village is not far. I am going directly there. Join me when you are ready.\"',NULL,NULL),(30,2,NULL,'Villagers!','Story',9,7,91,28.8,3,3,'We followed the cavern east and north for a while, until we came upon a few villagers. All but two of them had passed out on the ground. They were disoriented, and had little idea of how they had gotten here. The spores were lighter here, compared to the chamber across the water, but still present.\n\nWe woke the others, and arranged to carry them out. There were 11 in total, and each of us could carry two at a time. It would only take a couple trips. However, in talking to the villagers more, we learned there should be 16 of them in total.\n\nWe decided to prioritize on the 11 we had found so far, and after getting them out, continued our search for the remaining five.',NULL,NULL),(31,2,NULL,'Rocks','CollectStone',2,1,19,10.2,3,3,'We crossed the great cavern, finding little else but rocks, until we came to a narrow passage...',NULL,NULL),(32,2,NULL,'Narrow Passage','CollectStone',3,2,30.4,18.3,3,3,'We squeezed our way through the narrow tunnel, single-file, for several hours.',NULL,NULL),(33,2,NULL,'Missing Villagers','Story',1,NULL,7.7,24.2,3,3,'We followed some of the villagers just inside the cave. They proceeded nervously, hand to the wall, looking back over their shoulder to make sure the cave\'s entrance was still visible.\n\nApproaching a bend, we told the villagers to head back, and continued on our own. A little later, we reached a large cavern. We searched it in its entirety, and found the remains of a makeshift camp: an small fire pit. Some villagers had certainly been this way...',NULL,NULL),(34,2,NULL,'Exploring South','CollectStone',11,6,61,37.6,3,3,NULL,NULL,'Right'),(35,2,118,'An Unfamiliar Figure','Story',12,11,49.8,41.6,3,3,'In the dark, we saw a figure hunched over some bones. As we drew near, it stood up and faced us.\n\nIt was a creature, short, and fungal. But not covered in mushrooms: it was, itself, a great mushroom, with a face, and arms, and a mouth. It spoke:\n\n\"Don\'t worry: these are not the bones of your people. They are of bats, eaten by a creature that lives in this cave. It was once a quiet creature, but the sounds of your people have... excited it.\"\n\nWe stood for a moment, unsure what to say, or do. This was not a creature of the gods... but could it be an Unraveller?\n\n\"We would have preferred to have remained hidden, but... well... it is not my place to say. Go, and forget you saw us, or follow me, and meet my people.\"\n\nThe creature turned and walked deeper into the cave.',NULL,NULL),(36,2,NULL,'Colony of Bats','HuntAutoScaling',4,3,41.4,18,3,3,'In the tunnel, we accidentally disturbed a sleeping colony of bats. They awoke, scared, and screaming. With nowhere to run, we were forced to fight.\n\nWe emerged, at last, from the tunnel, covered in dust, scratches, and bits of hair.',NULL,NULL),(37,2,NULL,'Movement in the Dark','Story',5,4,58.4,24.9,3,3,'We entered a large cavern filled with stalagmites and stalactites. Weaving our way through it, we heard movement. Not of a small creature - not a bat - but something larger, human-sized, and on the ground. We looked around, but saw nothing.\n\nClearing the stalactites, the cavern opened up; on our left was a large, underwater cave; perfectly still, like a mirror.\n\nWe hadn\'t seen the creature responsible for the sounds earlier, nor any sign of the lost villagers. Had our ears been playing tricks on us? Had the villagers not come this way at all? Or perhaps what we had heard earlier was a predator, to which the villagers fell prey...\n\nWe decided to camp for a while on the edge of the lake. We watched and listened for any signs of life, but none made themselves known to us.\n\nAfter washing ourselves a little, we resumed our journey.',NULL,NULL),(38,2,NULL,'','CollectStone',22,21,55.2,67.6,3,3,'As we traveled, we came to a narrow space between an underground lake and the cavern wall. Cave mushrooms grew here, and they appeared to be getting denser as we continued.','SmallMushrooms',NULL),(39,2,NULL,'Undergound Village','CollectStone',23,22,70.1,67.8,3,3,'We arrived at the outskirts of a city populated by inhabitants of all sizes, most tiny mushrooms, but a few our size, like the one we had met earlier.\n\nThough the smaller ones seemed to give us a wide berth, we began walking more carefully.',NULL,NULL),(40,2,NULL,'Cave Mushrooms','Story',6,5,69.6,31.2,3,3,'We found a patch of large mushrooms. The air was heavy with their spores, and though we were immune to their effects, we were sure a mortal would not be so lucky.\n\nSearching the area, we found signs that villagers had been through here: trampled mushrooms, and a backpack at the edge of the lake, its contents scattered on the ground. Had the villagers crossed the water here, or continued through the cave to the south?\n\n---\n\nWhen we had the time, we took a sample of the mushrooms outside, to examine them more-closely. It seems their spores are deadened by the sunlight, and the flesh itself does not seem toxic. Their flavor, however, is unpleasant, and not much improved through cooking. If there is a practical use for these mushrooms, we have not been able to find one.','SmallMushrooms',NULL),(41,2,NULL,'Hidden Passage','CollectStone',15,13,15.4,47.1,3,3,'We followed the mushroom-person to the far end of the cavern. It seemed as though we were headed to a wall, but as we drew nearer we could see there was, in fact, a narrow passage. The shape of the rocks, as they were approached from this angle, hid it well; an illusion that appeared to have resulted naturally.',NULL,NULL),(42,2,NULL,'All Accounted For','Story',10,9,94,13.2,3,3,'We followed the passage to its end, and found the remaining villagers lying amidst mushrooms. Three were unconscious, barely breathing; the other two had died.\n\nWe carried all five back to the village, where they were received with cries of relief, and sadness.\n\n---\n\nThe villagers put up signs warning of the danger of the caves, and thanked us for our help.','BigBasicChest',NULL),(43,2,NULL,'','CollectStone',21,17,37.5,70,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(44,2,NULL,'Hundun','WanderingMonster',14,13,28.3,36.7,3,3,'We followed the sounds of the creature into a den. Thinking we had been undetected, we began to circle the creature, but it must have had the sixth sense, for as soon as we began to split up, it leapt at me.\n\nThough we had underestimated its ability, it had also underestimated ours... and more grievously. I rolled out of the way as my companions attacked it from either side. The creature fell dead, cut into three pieces.\n\nIt would have pleased the perfectionist in me if each piece had two of the beast\'s legs, but the attack was not so clean. A little cleaner than I was, however: a large amount of the creature\'s blood had been cast in my direction, and it covered the back of my head, and neck, and was running down my right arm and side. It caused an itching sensation which would probably have registered as searing pain to mortal flesh.\n\nThis was, indeed, an effective guardian. Had any villager come this way, they would have certainly been killed, even without the delirium induced by the preceding mushroom fields.','RubyChest','Bottom'),(45,2,NULL,'Exploring East','CollectStone',7,6,80.1,33.7,3,3,'We crossed the river and looked around, but all we saw were rocks.',NULL,NULL),(46,2,NULL,'Gold Vein','MineGold',8,7,71.2,44,3,3,'Nothing alive was found to the south - not even those mushrooms - but we did happen upon a vein of exposed Gold.',NULL,NULL),(47,2,NULL,'Growing Up','Story',24,23,84,62.4,3,3,'A small mushroom-person approached us, and handed us an even-smaller (and non-sentient) mushroom.\n\n\"Take good care of it. It will grow up.\"\n\nThen they left.\n\n---\n\nWhen we took the mushroom outside, it did grow, and quickly. In a matter of days, it was even taller than we are!\n\nFortunately, it did not maintain this pace of growth, but some of us wonder if it might one day grow arms, and legs, and begin moving about.\n\nI suppose only time can tell...','LargeMushroom',NULL),(48,2,NULL,'First Contact','Story',25,23,81.9,84.4,3,3,'\"Ah hum!\" A large mushroom-person greeted us. \"This day was inevitable, we supposed. We\'re sure you have many questions for us, as do we of you. Come, let us speak for a while, and consider yourselves as guests; our first in over 1000 years.\"\n\nWe were invited into a large building which, on the inside, was carved and decorated in a way which felt purposeful, but following the principles of an aesthetics which was alien to us. Despite that, even we could feel that this building was one of great importance, and as living mushrooms of every size began to gather, there was a nervousness that reminded us of our mortal life.\n\nThe giant mushroom spoke at length about its people - which it called Puturu - and asked many questions about ours. When we explained our divine provenance, the great mushroom seemed to have a sort of understanding. We got the impression that though the Puturu had been isolated from the rest of the world for some time, they carried a large body of ancient knowledge with them.\n\n---\n\nSatisfied, at last, the mushroom proposed a sort of treaty: they wished to be left relatively alone, and promised no harm or conflict between our people.\n\n\"Finally,\" the huge mushroom said, \"if you will have it, take this young Puturu with you.\"\n\nA human-sized mushroom emerged from the crowd, a smile on its face.\n\n\"Russula will serve by your side, and through working together, perhaps we can learn more about one another.\"\n\nWe accepted, extending our deepest gratitude, and left the village.\n\n---\n\nThe Puturu are a curious people; direct, polite, knowledgable, and our lord has shown interest in them, as well. It seems there is still much to learn about this world.',NULL,'Right'),(49,2,119,'Living Amethyst','TreasureHunt',20,19,17.5,93.2,3,3,'At last, we found the source of the magic: an exposed ley line, sustaining a large growth of minerals, primarily amethyst.\n\nWe harvested some of the crystals at the edge of the growth. Even these required the divine manifestation of Metal to cut free.\n\nMost of the gems we cut would only be worth some coins, but a few were much more valuable, interwoven with pure Quintessence.','CrystallizedQuint',NULL),(50,2,NULL,'Bones','CollectStone',13,12,35.8,46.7,3,3,'We followed the mushroom-person in silence, when, suddenly, it stopped. We heard a shuffling noise nearby, and then the sound of a creature running. We couldn\'t see it, but from the sounds its feet made on the cavern floor, it was heavy, and had six legs.\n\n\"That was the creature I spoke of. We call it \'Hundun\'. It has no head, but that will not prevent it from eating you. Dangerous to keep around, but it was a convenient guardian. Now that we are discovered, Hundun no longer has a purpose. If it will please you in some way to dispatch of it, I will not stop you.\"',NULL,NULL),(51,3,NULL,'The Sea Floor','Story',1,NULL,15.5,7.7,3,3,'We hiked to the edge of the sea, barely a day from the city, and entered. Using our divine gifts, were were able to push the water around us as we traveled, giving us a small pocket of air, and by forcing bubbling around the edge of the pocket, we were even able to circulate in breathable - if not rather fishy - air.\n\nThe meeting-point for the prince was a short hike from the shore. After getting our bearings, we began the journey.',NULL,NULL),(52,3,NULL,'Kelp Forest','Gather',2,1,29.6,12.2,3,3,'Uncertain as to whether or not it would be offensive to hunt the fish in this region, we contented ourselves with harvesting kelp to eat.',NULL,NULL),(53,3,120,'Shipwreck','TreasureHunt',3,2,9.2,22.1,3,3,'We explored a sunken ship, not far from land. Looters had definitely been here before, but we were able to easily reach places which would have been difficult for them, and found some small treasure.','GoldChest',NULL),(54,3,NULL,'The Prince','Story',4,2,42.4,14.1,3,3,'We met the prince at the appointed spot. He was accompanied by guards - a couple octopi with spears that looked as sharp as shark\'s teeth.\n\nThey were all sparsely dressed; what they did wear was very sleek, no doubt optimized for swimming speed and agility.\n\n\"Ah, there they are,\" the prince exclaimed, approaching us. \"What powerful auras. And such a creative use of your power,\" he added, motioning towards our frothing pocket of air. \"I think I\'ll be more comfortable out here, if you don\'t mind.\"\n\nWe nodded.\n\nThe prince turned toward his guards. \"Go ahead to the castle without me, and alert my king that his son will be slightly delayed.\"\n\n\"My prince,\" one of the guards said, \"the king has said to remain with you the entire way.\"\n\n\"Pshaw! What can you do that these fine Vassals cannot? I can think of one thing only: swim very quickly, and the best use for that ability would be to tell my father that his son will be slightly delayed, so that he have no need to worry!\"\n\n\"Yes, prince,\" the guard said.\n\nThey bowed, and swam off.\n\nAfter a moment, the prince spoke up.\n\n\"Much better! Those two are very loyal, to be sure, but not very good conversationalists. Which reminds me: I\'d love to hear about your kingdom on the land! I have so many questions!\"\n\nThe prince began to swim, and we followed, indulging his every question.',NULL,'Left'),(55,3,NULL,'Snacking','HuntAutoScaling',5,4,55.4,16.2,3,3,'While we were traveling, the prince swam out to get a snack. We were a little surprised to see him return with some fish in his mouth. Noticing our surprise, the Prince assured us \"if it can\'t talk, you can eat it.\"\n\nWe detected a hint of sarcasm in his voice, however. The rules were probably more nuanced than he was telling us.',NULL,NULL),(56,3,NULL,'Sand and Ink','Story',6,5,67.9,14,3,3,'Abamātu\'s kingdom was faintly visible in the distance as we stopped for sleep. The prince had been relatively quiet today, apparently having no further questions for us.\n\nThat night, we slept under cover of a rock that jutted out of the ocean floor, taking turns to watch.\n\nThe ocean at night is so much more alive than the land. While there is plenty that is nocturnal on land, it is mostly smaller creatures; here, sharks and other large beasts drift by at all hours, eyes wide open, looking for a meal, or to avoid becoming one.\n\nAnd so I was not alarmed, during my watch, to hear a wooshing sound pass on the other side of the rock. What _was_ surprising was the soft laughter that followed - voices I didn\'t recognize! I called out for my companions, and rushed into the water for the prince, but was too late: sand and black ink swirled everywhere around us, and from somewhere to the south we heard the fading words of the prince: \"Apologies, good Vassals! Please tell the king his son has other plans this year!\"',NULL,NULL),(57,3,NULL,'The Reef','HuntAutoScaling',7,6,61.1,24.8,3,3,'We followed the direction the prince had gone. It was much harder to find a trail in the ocean; fortunately, we came to a wall of coral reef with one obvious path through it. Unless the prince wished to swim close to the surface, where he\'d be more-easily spotted, he would have taken this path...',NULL,NULL),(58,3,NULL,'','HuntAutoScaling',8,7,57,37.4,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(59,3,NULL,'Purple Plants','Gather',9,8,40.4,32.5,3,3,'Strange, purple plants grew from the coral here. We harvested some, and ate.',NULL,'Left'),(60,3,121,'Lobsters','HuntAutoScaling',10,9,24.6,27.7,3,3,NULL,NULL,'Left'),(61,3,NULL,'Detritus','TreasureHunt',11,8,66,50.3,3,3,'We found some detritus nestled in the reef. Searching it, we found a water-logged chest.','BigBasicChest','Left'),(62,3,NULL,'Stinging Eels!','WanderingMonster',12,8,46.8,50.6,3,3,'While making our way through the maze-like coral, some eels identified us as being a bit out of our element, and attempted to make a snack of us. They were easily dispatched, of course, but still a nuisance.',NULL,'Top'),(63,3,NULL,'','Gather',13,12,35,56.2,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(64,3,NULL,'Bones...','TreasureHunt',14,13,25.3,44.1,3,3,'We found the bones of some great creature. At first we thought it might be those of a whale, but the skull - what little of it we could find - had strange features...\n\nWe decided to take some home, for further study.','SkeletalRemains','Right'),(65,3,NULL,'','Story',15,13,20,59.3,3,3,'Finally out of the reef, we stopped to rest, and empty our boots of the sand that perpetually filled them.\n\nWhile we did so, we spotted a long piece of cloth - a scarf, or perhaps a belt - amidst sweeping lines in the sand. The cloth was too vibrant in color to have been here long, but it wasn\'t something the prince had been wearing.\n\nStill, it was our only lead.\n\nThe lines didn\'t go far, but they went generally south. We rested for a brief moment, then continued our search.',NULL,'Top'),(66,3,NULL,'Underwater Vents','HuntAutoScaling',16,15,17.4,71.6,3,3,'We came upon hot, underwater vents, and the entrance to a dark cave. Strange creatures dwelt here, of which we ate a few before entering the cave...',NULL,'Top'),(67,3,NULL,'','CollectStone',17,16,31.4,75.6,3,3,'The fumes emanating from the vent were foul-smelling, but we forced our way through.\n\nThen, from up ahead, we heard a pained voice! The prince?\n\nWe rushed forward.',NULL,'Right'),(68,3,NULL,'Wounds','Story',18,17,38.3,90.5,3,3,'We ran forward as fast as we could, and found the prince. He was holding another of his kind in his arms - a friend?\n\nThey were both covered in soot and sand, but the one in the prince\'s arms was badly burned, and breathing heavily. One of the hot vents must have caught them by surprise.\n\nThe prince looked up at us. \"I\'m sorry for running off, but there\'s no time: please, help me carry him home. This is my best friend, and he needs attention. Soon.\"\n\nWe tore some of our clothes to use as bandages, and wrapped his friend\'s wounds as best we could, then picked him up. The prince was startled by our strength, but continued.\n\n\"He needs to be kept in water, or he\'ll dry out. Can you keep your bubble around your heads, only? I\'m so sorry. I promise you\'ll be well-compensated when we get home.\"\n\nWe assured him that any compensation would be handled by our respective kings.\n\n\"Thank you. There\'s a path through this cave that leads home. It will be faster than going back through the reef. I\'ll scout ahead to look for predators, but I promise I won\'t leave your sight again.\"\n\nWe adjusted our pocket of air, and let the water permeate our clothes.\n\nIt would be a difficult hike.',NULL,NULL),(69,3,NULL,'Stories','MineGold',19,18,54,84.8,3,3,'We stopped to rest, and asked the prince about his friend.\n\nThey were apparently \"friends since hatching\", and had gone to school together for many years.\n\nThe prince told a few stories of the pair\'s misadvantures together, and we gathered the prince was not very fond of being prince, or the duties that came with that title.\n\nHis friend wakened, interrupting the prince\'s stories. The prince attempted to explain the situation to him, but it\'s not clear how much got through before sleep took over his mind again.\n\nWe did our best to reassure the prince, and continued our journey.',NULL,NULL),(70,3,NULL,'','Gather',20,19,69,83.7,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(71,3,NULL,'','Gather',21,20,73.5,67.9,3,3,NULL,NULL,'Right'),(72,3,NULL,'At the Gates','Story',22,21,89.4,52.4,3,3,'As we approached the gates, some guards approached us.\n\n\"My prince, you\'re late,\" one of the guards said. \"The king demands your presence immediately.\"\n\n\"Tell him I\'m not available!\" Snapped the prince. \"Help us get this man to the hospital,\" he pointed towards us, \"or get out of my way!\"\n\n\"Of course, my prince,\" the guard said, and nodded to his inferiors. One swam off into the castle, and two others came to help us with the prince\'s wounded friend.\n\n\"We\'re going with you,\" the prince ordered. \"I will not leave his side until he\'s safe.\"',NULL,'Top'),(73,3,122,'Hospital','Story',23,22,82.3,31.3,3,3,'The guards were able to transport the prince\'s friend with much greater ease than we, rendering our help obsolete. We sensed the prince still desired our presence, however, and so we followed them to what was apparently a hospital.\n\nThe prince stopped us outside. \"I\'m afraid I can avoid my father no longer. I\'ll swim ahead to speak to him, and explain the situation. Join us when you can. And thank you again. I owe you.\"',NULL,'Right'),(74,3,123,'The Prince','Story',25,24,80.5,15.7,3,3,'After seeing the king, a guard approached us.\n\n\"The prince requests you at the western gate.\"\n\n---\n\nAs we approached the gate, the prince waved at us.\n\nWe approached.\n\n\"This is the gate you should have entered,\" he said, motioning toward it, \"several days ago, and with much less trouble to yourselves. I can\'t apologize, or thank you enough, but I suppose I can try: sorry, and thank you, sincerely.\"\n\nHe bowed at us.\n\n\"My friend is doing well. I\'m going to visit him shortly, but I wanted to say goodbye to you, first. I have a gift for you, but do not think that this is the extent of my gratitude. You\'ll see me again, when I\'ve thought of a way to properly repay an immortal.\"\n\nHe smiled. \"Until then,\" then swam away.',NULL,'Right'),(75,3,NULL,'The King','Story',24,23,91.8,12.4,3,3,'The king received us - a great octopus sprawled across his throne. The room was otherwise largely empty. Ornately decorated, but mostly just large. We were stopped while still a considerable distance from the king - this was apparently as close as we were allowed - and then he spoke.\n\nWe expected him to ask about our mission, or the events that transpired, but he barely mentioned them, instead bestowing a generic, royal thanks for our service to his kingdom. No mention of our lord was made, either; it seemed this reception was a formality which was being exercised specifically for us.\n\nIt didn\'t last but a few minutes, and at the end of it, a servant gave us a gift.\n\nWe accepted it, bowed, and took our leave.','CupOfLife',NULL),(76,4,NULL,'','CollectStone',24,23,70.4,31.8,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(77,4,NULL,'','Gather',14,13,13.9,74.2,3,3,'Increasingly confident that the purple grass was safely edible, we gathered some as we traveled.','PurpleGrass','Bottom'),(78,4,NULL,'','Gather',15,14,13.6,86.2,3,3,NULL,'PurpleGrass','Bottom'),(79,4,NULL,'','CollectStone',6,5,43.4,42.9,3,3,'We followed the rift south for a while, looking for a crossing. It did seem to be getting narrower as we went.',NULL,'Bottom'),(80,4,NULL,'','CollectStone',7,6,54.1,49.6,3,3,NULL,NULL,'Bottom'),(81,4,NULL,'The Fisherman','Story',4,3,44.1,11,3,3,'As we approached the ravine, we passed a small hut at the foot of the mountain. Curious, we approached, and a figure emerged, and ran toward us.\n\nIt was one of the dead, and though we knew it to be harmless, something deep within us - some remnant of our mortal lives - found the creature disturbing.\n\nWhether it had lost its senses in life or in death, we were not sure. It gibbered incomprehensibly, pointing toward the ravine. It seemed to want us to follow.\n\nSince we were headed that way, anyway, we followed the creature. It lead us to a scrap of cloth at the edge of the ravine, where a fishing rod had been planted.\n\nWe approached, and looked down. This was not just a ravine in the underworld, but a rift in creation itself; beyond the distant stars visible in the rift, we could feel the horror of nothingness, and the chaos that lay just beyond; the edge of creation itself.\n\nWhat could have left such a scar in the underworld? Could the wars have been this destructive?\n\n---\n\nLooking across the rift, we saw a glowing mountain range in the distance. The way it caught the light, we thought it must be covered in ice, or perhaps be a glacier. Though if it was ice, great power would be needed to keep it frozen in this hot place.\n\nBased on our lord\'s description, we were sure that the mountain range was our destination, but with no way to cross the rift, we would have to find an alternate route.\n\nBefore we could go, the dead creature handed us a small bag; fish it had apparently caught in the rift. Though we were not sure it could understand us, we thanked it, and moved on.','FishBag',NULL),(82,4,124,'The Graveyard\'s Keeper','Story',20,19,77.1,92,3,3,'We decided to explore the graveyard, and entered. A great field of gravestones, almost every one identical to the other, went as far as the eye could see.\n\nFollowing a worn path, we found a house occupied by the graveyard\'s keeper.\n\nHappy for some company, he served us food and drink, and gave us a tour of some of the more-interesting features of the graveyard.',NULL,NULL),(83,4,NULL,'Lightning Tower','TreasureHunt',16,15,25.2,94.5,3,3,'At last, we reached the source of the glow: a great tower which spat blue bolts of lightning. We used our divine gifts to shield ourselves, and explored the tower.\n\nIt appeared to be only recently abandoned: there was a thin layer of dust, and some of the machinery within was still operating, powered by crystals which had been mined from the mountains nearby.\n\nAs we ascended the floors of the tower, the bolts became more frequent, and more intense. Not wishing to risk injury that might delay our mission, we gave up reaching the top, and left, grabbing some of the crystals on our way out.','CrystallizedQuint',NULL),(84,4,NULL,'An Enormous Tibia','TreasureHunt',8,7,64.1,56.4,3,3,'As we continued south, the number and size of the bones increased. We had entered some kind of bone graveyard, but of what kind of creature, we could not guess.\n\nClimbing over pieces of broken bone, we occasionally sent one tumbling into the rift.\n\nUp ahead, the mountain range curved to block our progress, and was then interrupted only by the rift, into which the range had collapsed. The remaining rock appeared unstable. We agreed we would have to turn back.\n\n---\n\nBefore leaving, we found an enormous tibia in relatively good shape, and took it. At least this would be interesting to show to the others, back home.','EnormousTibia','Right'),(85,4,NULL,'Crossing the Rift','Story',18,17,53,76.4,3,3,'We reached the narrowest part of the rift that blocked our progress. The ground here felt unstable, shaken by light, but frequent, earthquakes.\n\nAfter a few false starts, we found a path to the other side, and continued our journey.',NULL,'Left'),(86,4,NULL,'Emissaries','Story',21,19,84.1,61.7,3,3,'Traveling north, we met a large company of armed men lead by two divine figures: immortals, like ourselves.\n\nWe approached, hoping to engage in casual conversation, but were met with mockery and disdain.\n\nThe immortals served the two eldest children of the god Ashur, and, like us, were sent to introduce themselves to the new goddess of the underworld.\n\nIn their eyes, we were immortals of an insignificant god, and therefore insignificant ourselves. They commanded us to leave them, threatening to take our offering to the queen if we did not.\n\nNot wishing to risk a fight, we remained silent, and moved on...',NULL,NULL),(87,4,125,'The Throng & The Mark','Story',25,24,82.5,21,3,3,'As we approached the softly-shining palace, we began to see more and more creatures heading toward it. Spirits of varying shapes, sizes, and domains; a few of the mortal species, like ourselves, blessed with divinity; and countless dead.\n\nAnd between us all and the palace was a crystal wall manned with soldiers of the new goddess. No creature, it seemed, would be allowed to enter.\n\n---\n\nAfter speaking with a deer spirit named Nahlu, we learned that there were a few stations along the wall where gifts were being accepted for the new goddess. Seeing no other option, we found one of these stations. A huge line had formed at it, filled with other beings who wished to make an offering to the goddess.\n\nWe waited in the line for several hours. When it was our turn, the process was fast and efficient, observing only a minimum of the usual ceremony for such an offering.\n\nWe could not help but worry whether our lord\'s offering would ever make it to the new goddess...\n\n---\n\nWith nothing more to do, we returned to the world of the living, happy to leave the sands, rocks, and heat of the underworld behind us.\n\nIt seemed we could escape it entirely, however: our long exposure to the swirling chaos of the rifts had left a mark on us, and through us, our lord. Though it did not seem harmful, we sensed it was not something that would simply fade away, and could not help but wonder what long-term effects it might have...',NULL,NULL),(88,4,NULL,'Oasis in the Land of the Dead','HuntAutoScaling',12,11,26.3,50.6,3,3,'We decided to explore the valley to the east. To our surprise, the plants appeared to be from the land of the living. How they came to be here, we could not guess. Exposure to chaos from the rifts? An attack against the unliving during the long wars that took place here? Who could say.\n\nYet more surprising, we found an entire ecosystem of creatures here, including a lake that at times seemed to contain more fish than water.\n\nWe took the opportunity to fish, hunt, and recover ourselves before continuing our dreary journey through the grey sands of the underworld.',NULL,NULL),(89,4,NULL,'A Strange Glow','Story',13,11,27.8,69.7,3,3,'We continued south and west, into another desert of sharp sand. To the east, the great rift appeared to be at its narrowest, and we hoped to find a way to cross.\n\nTo the south we saw a strange glow over the mountains, and wondered what the source of it might be. Having tested the purple plants we harvested earlier, we knew they were not dangerous is small quantities, but shared concerns about trekking through them for many hours at a time. We would have to find a clearer path if we wanted to investigate the glow.',NULL,'Top'),(90,4,NULL,'','CollectStone',17,13,41.7,70.8,3,3,'We entered another desert of sharp sand as we traveled west, featureless except for the occasional rock or boulder.',NULL,'Top'),(91,4,NULL,'','CollectStone',10,9,10.7,43.6,3,3,'As we approached an isolated rift, we decided to take a brief rest near it. Some part of our curiosity must have gotten the better of us. Fortunately, we did not stay long enough for temptation to take hold of our senses, and we continued our journey.\n\nNot an hour later, we found a break in the mountains, and turned south. At last, we were back on track.',NULL,NULL),(92,4,NULL,'An Iron Gate','CollectStone',19,18,76.1,73.9,3,3,'As we traveled, we saw a large graveyard to the south. It was surrounded by an old, iron fence that went for miles.\n\nAfter walking along the fence for hours, we saw a gate, and considered entering before continuing our journey.',NULL,NULL),(93,4,NULL,'','CollectStone',2,1,20.1,16.8,3,3,'As we traveled west, we passed smoking volcanoes which occasionally spewed lava. The ground around us was smooth rock, no doubt formed from a larger eruption. We hoped another such eruption would not happen any time soon...\n\n---\n\nIn the distance ahead, we saw a great ravine which stretched north and south. Hopefully we would find some way to cross it.',NULL,NULL),(94,4,NULL,'To the West','CollectStone',9,5,25.1,33.9,3,3,'Blocked by the rift to the east, and mountains to the south, we had little option but to turn west, and hope a path would eventually open up for us...',NULL,NULL),(95,4,NULL,'Purple Plants','Story',11,10,17.3,58.2,3,3,'Clear of the mountains, a great plain stretched out before us. Plants grew here: enormous blades of purple grass spread west, while below us, to the east, we saw a lush valley.\n\nWe stopped to gather some of the grass before continuing.','PurpleGrass',NULL),(96,4,NULL,'Sharp Sands','CollectStone',5,4,36.6,27.6,3,3,'',NULL,NULL),(97,4,NULL,'','Gather',22,21,92,48,3,3,NULL,'PurpleGrass',NULL),(98,4,NULL,'','CollectStone',23,22,81.4,38,3,3,'Over the hills, we saw the glowing mountain range again. It was too clear to be ice. Glass, or some crystal, perhaps.\n\nWe knew for certain now that this was our destination; the home of the new goddess of the underworld.',NULL,NULL),(99,4,NULL,'Bearing Gifts','Story',1,NULL,5.6,20.8,3,3,'Our lord has not sent us empty-handed, of course: as a gift to the new goddess, we carry with us a great, golden casket. The contents are unknown to us, but we\'ve been told to transport it with the utmost care...',NULL,NULL),(100,4,NULL,'','CollectStone',3,2,32.9,14.7,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(101,5,NULL,'Shipwreck','RemixShipwreck',1,NULL,28,30.75,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(102,5,NULL,'Beach','RemixBeach',2,1,15.5,41.8,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(103,5,NULL,'A Small Cave','RemixTreasureRoom',3,2,20.05,49.25,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(104,5,NULL,'Beach','RemixBeach',4,1,45.5,17.4,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(105,5,NULL,'Island Forest','RemixForest',5,4,29.05,10.55,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(106,5,NULL,'Cave Entrance','RemixCave',6,4,53,19.5,3,3,NULL,NULL,'Left'),(107,5,NULL,'Fork in the Cave','RemixCave',7,6,60.5,37.75,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(108,5,NULL,'Underground Lake','RemixUndergroundLake',8,7,56.84,43.95,3,3,NULL,NULL,'Right'),(109,5,NULL,'An Opening','RemixCave',9,7,67.39,60.89,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(110,5,NULL,'Endless Stone','RemixCave',10,9,53.34,72.26,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(111,5,NULL,'A Clearly-magic Tower','RemixMagicTower',11,10,33.17,84.85,3,3,NULL,NULL,'Right'),(112,5,NULL,'Strange Plants','RemixUmbralPlants',12,11,43.36,95.24,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(113,5,NULL,'Underground Village','RemixDarkVillage',13,10,66.46,81.4,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(114,5,NULL,'Underground Foothills','RemixCave',14,13,53.26,85.24,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(115,5,NULL,'Graveyard','RemixGraveyard',15,13,67.37,96.1,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(116,5,NULL,'Precipice','RemixCave',16,13,82.57,77.71,3,3,NULL,NULL,NULL),(117,5,NULL,'The Deep','RemixTheDeep',17,16,85.67,88.1,3,3,NULL,NULL,'Bottom');
