INSERT INTO `pet_species` VALUES (1,'Desikh','monotreme/desikh','An unusually-intelligent monotreme.\r\n\r\nScientists have yet to determine the function of its arm-like appendage, though there is evidence to suggest that it serves some purpose in Desikh mating rituals.',0.3125,0.71875,78,0,0,1,0,'spotted',0.5375,0.2583333,-5,1,34,'monotreme','Desikh',NULL),(2,'Roundish','mammal/roundish','In nature, this round creature is often confused for a vase. It uses this disguise to avoid detection by predators, which are largely unaware of the existence of vases, and so pay it no attention whatsoever.',0.8125,0.6875,-5,1,0,1,1,NULL,0.46041,0.36875,-5,1,34,'mammal','Roundish',NULL),(3,'Cotton Candy','elemental/cotton-candy','Animated cotton candy. How the first one came to be is unknown, but there is evidence that the species has been on Earth for tens of thousands of years.',0.5,0.5,-85,0,0,1,0,'speckled',0.71041,0.26875,10,0,1358,'elemental','Cotton Candy','A lumpy creature with no discernible limbs. Its face sits low on its body, which is a little taller than it is wide.'),(4,'Chickie','bird/chickie','This bird perpetually has the appearance of a young chick, though it is a separate species from the common chicken.',0.625,0.875,8,0,0,1,0,'speckled-small',0.39791,0.6083333,-30,1,144,'bird','Chickie',NULL),(5,'Mole','mammal/mole','Just a run-of-the-mill mole.',0.28125,0.859375,-45,1,0,1,1,NULL,0.45,0.54,-10,1,34,'mammal','Mole',NULL),(6,'Oft','bird/odd-flying-thing','It\'s said that, for a while, no one had a name for this rare creature, and that it came to be colloquially known as an \"odd flying thing\"; that it went so long without an \"official\" name, that the unofficial one stuck, but was often abbreviated as \"OFT\" in publications, to save on typing.\r\n\r\nThat\'s what\'s said, anyway.',0.671875,0.546875,148,1,0,1,0,'striped-small',0.4083333,0.4125,-40,1,144,'bird','Oft','A small ball with smaller wings and even smaller feet.\n\nWait, this is a bird, right? Where is its bill??'),(7,'Triangle','elemental/triangle','A being of pure, euclidean triangleness. Some people say that this creature\'s existence is evidence in support of simulationism, but this view is not widely accepted.',0.203125,0.90625,-3,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.516666,0.575,0,1,108,'elemental','Triangle',NULL),(8,'Fish with Legs','amphibian/ba-ha','It isn\'t the first time this has happened in nature. It probably won\'t be the last.',0.125,0.725,-15,1,0,1,0,'spotted',0.416666,0.4875,-5,1,35,'amphibian','Fish with Legs','You could mistake it for a common fish - like maybe one of those puffy-lipped ones - except it\'s got those long, stick legs!'),(9,'Mousie','mammal/much-cuter-mousie','Though bearing a striking resemblance to the common _Mus musculus_, the two species rarely produce offspring successfully; when they do, it\'s always infertile.\r\n\r\nYou know, like that whole horse/donkey/mule thing.',0.67083333,0.4416666,-45,1,0,1,1,NULL,0.33541,0.68125,5,1,34,'mammal','Mousie','This creature _actually_ looks like a regular-ass mouse!\r\n\r\nTruly, and quite literally, exceptional among the species available in Poppy Seed Pets.'),(10,'Mushroom','fungus/mushroom','Fungi have been on the earth for so long, it\'s no surprise that at least _one_ species gained sentience...',0.4,0.84375,-22,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.47916666,0.5625,-10,1,61,'fungus','Mushroom',NULL),(11,'Bunny','mammal/bunny','For once, a normal animal! It\'s just a straight-up bunny that looks exactly like all bunnies do!',0.62083333,0.947916666,30,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.63125,0.59375,-10,1,34,'mammal','Bunny',NULL),(12,'Peacock','bird/bi-colored-peacock','Locals spoke of an enormous bird with a beak as bright as the sun. They called it the \"firebill\", and seeing one was considered to be enormously-good luck. Explorers, eager to see this amazing creature for themselves, searched every corner of the island, but the closest they found was this peacock. (Could people really have confused bright tail-feathers for a bright bill, though??)',0.3333,0.375,-175,1,0,1,0,'spotted',0.47916666,0.3,5,1,144,'bird','Peacock',NULL),(13,'A.D.','elemental/a-d','Not much is known about this creature. Unquestionably a eukaryote, its ancestors seem to be closely related to animals, though it shares some unexpected traits with slime molds...\r\n\r\nHow it hovers is anyone\'s guess.\r\n\r\nFriendly little things, at any rate!',0.25416666,0.50625,10,1,0,1,1,NULL,0.5125,0.4,5,1,108,'elemental','A.D.','A round body with four protruding... limbs? At least two appear to be used as hands; the others might be ears... or maybe they\'re all hands?? Or maybe they\'re all ears??!?'),(14,'Sneqo','lizard/sneqo','Wait, there are snakes... _with arms?_\r\n\r\nGAME. OVER.',0.4083333,0.6083333,80,0,0,1,0,'striped',0.52083333,0.12,-12,1,35,'lizard','Sneqo',NULL),(15,'Bulbun','mammal/bulbun','It\'s fortunate that the \"Bulbun\" (Lagomorpha Bulbosae) has no natural predators: it has no defensive mechanisms to speak of, save a mildly-unpleasant, yeasty flavor.',0.32708,0.7583333,-40,1,1,1,1,NULL,0.4875,0.425,0,1,34,'mammal','Bulbun','The Bulbun has a pear-shaped body topped with two, long ears, which it keeps upright except when hiding. It has a puff-ball tail, two short legs, and two arms which it keeps tucked underneath its long fur.'),(16,'Amalgam','slime/amalgam','Ugh.',0.53958,0.81458,-60,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.69375,0.67916666,20,1,301,'slime','Amalgam','A gooey pile dotted with small faces that never give an impression of being anything but merely content. Except for that at least one of the faces always seems to be sticking its tongue out.'),(17,'Hatoful','bird/hatoful','It\'s said that if lovers see this bird flying overhead during a sunshower, that they\'ll be together forever.\r\n\r\nThe lovers, I mean.\r\n\r\nNot the bird and the sunshower.',0.86041,0.7416666,43,0,0,1,0,'spotted',0.5083333,0.26458,-2,1,144,'bird','Hatoful','The Hatoful resembles many owls, though this is due to convergent evolution rather than shared ancestry. The arrangement of its feathers give its head and face the heart shape it\'s famous for.'),(18,'Short-tailed Pochard','bird/short-tailed-pochard','The Short-tailed Pochard, as its name suggests, is a species of duck with an unusually short tail.',0.72291,0.69375,30,0,1,1,0,'speckled-small',0.49583333,0.22,-20,1,144,'bird','Short-tailed Pochard','It looks like a common duck, but has a _really_ short tail.\n\nOh: and each of its legs is about twice the length of its body.'),(19,'Giraffalo','mammal/giraffalo','A descendant of the Giraffe, the Giraffalo sports impressively-sized horns. Biologists believe that in order to support such horns, the Giraffalo sacrificed some neck length. This would seem to give it a disadvantage when foraging, compared to a longer-necked Giraffe, however there are no Giraffes in the Hollow Earth. Something about the conditions of the Hollow Earth apparently favored horns over long necks.\r\n\r\nAnd then there\'s the opposable hooves, but that\'s a whole other thing.',0.225,0.6958,-11,1,0,1,1,NULL,0.39375,0.17291,2,1,34,'mammal','Giraffalo','A giraffe with buffalo-like antlers, a long, striped tail, and a polka dot-patterned coat.'),(20,'Rainbow Dolphin','mammal/rainbow-dolphin','It\'s super-colorful, _and_ it lives on land as easily as it does in water, so you can hang out with it all the time, _and_ it doesn\'t do that \"forced copulation\" thing! _Can dolphins get any better than this?!?_\r\n\r\nHint: the answer is \"no; no they can\'t!\"',0.3416666,0.2,0,1,0,1,1,NULL,0.47916666,0.40625,75,1,94,'mammal','Rainbow Dolphin',NULL),(21,'Unicorn','mammal/unicorn','Wikipedia describes the Unicorn as \"a legendary creature that has been described since antiquity as a beast with a single large, pointed, spiraling horn projecting from its forehead.\"\r\n\r\n\\*looks at unicorn\\*\r\n\r\nSure. Why not.',0.43125,0.81875,75,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.56,0.55,-1,1,34,'mammal','Unicorn',NULL),(22,'Star Monkey','mammal/star-monkey','Nocturnal hunters, they use the bioluminescent ends of their tails to attract prey.\r\n\r\nSo that\'s the \"star\" part, I guess, but don\'t monkeys have, like, arms? Generally-speaking?\r\n\r\nAnd _not_ hatch from eggs??\r\n\r\nAre these even mammals?!?!',0.75,0.75,40,0,1,0,0,'spotted-blue',0.60416666,0.415,0,0,34,'mammal','Star Monkey',NULL),(23,'Noombat','mammal/noombat','On earth, the Numbat eats almost exclusively termites, but its Hollow Earth-dwelling cousin - the Noombat - has adapted a wider appetite.\n\nHERG - the Hollow Earth Research Group - is currently conducting studies to determine whether or not introduction of the Noombat to Earth could help restore the populations of their endangered, Earth-dwelling cousins.',0.84583333,0.86666,50,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.82,0.66,0,1,34,'mammal','Noombat',NULL),(24,'Hexastrephidae','cephalopod/hexastrephidae','The Hexastrephidae is the only cephalopod known to have lips.\r\n\r\nIt\'s also one of the few creatures known to actually enjoy long walks on the beach.',0.59375,0.83541,60,0,0,1,0,'spotted',0.34375,0.4416666,15,1,142,'cephalopod','Hexastrephidae','The Hexastrephidae has a round body that sports a tuft for a tail, six tentacle legs, and a long neck that ends with a small head. It has bulging eyes, and a large sucker for a mouth, but still manages to look... well, not _exactly_ cute, but... it has its charm!'),(25,'Denebelly','mammal/star-belly','Named after the brightest star in the constellation Cygnus. How this sunken-eyed, pig-nosed creature came to be named after a beautiful, cosmic swan is anyone\'s guess.',0.69583333,0.65208,5,1,0,0,1,NULL,0.46458,0.22916666,-5,1,34,'mammal','Denebelly','It has a tallish, ovaloid body with a star-shaped marking prominently displayed on its stomach. Its small head is topped with a mess of hair, and two long, drooping, pointed ears. The short fur on the outside of its ears matches the shaggy fur of its nubbin tail. It has four, short legs, but when it sits, its legs are hidden under its body, much like a loafing cat\'s.'),(26,'Eggid','bird/eggid','Also known as \"Egg Kid\", this species keeps some of its egg as a sort of exoskeleton. As it ages, outer layers of the egg flake away as additional layers are built up from the inside, allowing it to grow with the pet.\r\n\r\nDo not attempt to remove the Eggid from its shell; like a clam, or snail, the body and shell are attached.',0.39375,0.81875,-40,1,0,1,0,'spotted',0.5583333,0.49,15,1,144,'bird','Eggid',NULL),(27,'Head','elemental/head','Is this, like, a person head? Is this pet just a human head that rolls around?\r\n\r\nThat\'s really weird, right? Like, you shouldn\'t just have something like that as a pet... right???',0.51875,0.95625,80,1,0,0,1,NULL,0.44375,0.5,-15,1,34,'elemental','Head',NULL),(28,'Tentacat','mammal/tentacat','Unlike most felines, the tentacat not only enjoys being in water, it cannot survive outside it.\r\n\r\n\"Does that mean that my house is also equipped with a large aquarium?\" you might wonder. But asking these sorts of questions leads to all kinds of trouble. Like how does it play Kin-ball with other pets? Or travel to the Umbra? Or mate with Cotton Candy pets? (Wouldn\'t the Cotton Candy dissolve?!) It\'s best just not to worry about these kinds of things... >_>',0.85,0.5916666,10,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.625,0.14375,0,1,253,'mammal','Tentacat',NULL),(29,'Catmouse','mammal/catmouse','Can\'t this game just have any normal cats in it?\r\n\r\nNo?\r\n\r\nAlright, then.',0.6666,0.825,45,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.51458,0.51041,0,1,34,'mammal','Catmouse','A lump with a face, pointed ears, a long tail, and tiny feet. Definitely looks more mouse than cat.'),(30,'Pegasus','mammal/pegasus','\"According to legend, everywhere a Pegasus strikes its hoof to the earth, an inspiring water spring burst forth.\"\r\n\r\nDoes that mean this isn\'t a real Pegasus, then?',0.3375,0.64583333,-15,1,0,1,1,NULL,0.46458,0.35,-5,1,144,'mammal','Pegasus','A horse head whose neck quickly tapers off into a tail. It\'s carried by its two large, leathery bat wings.'),(31,'Parrot','bird/parrot','Locals spoke of an enormous bird with a beak as bright as the sun. They called it the \"firebill\", and seeing one was considered to be enormously-good luck. Explorers, eager to see this amazing creature for themselves, searched every corner of the island, but the closest they found was this parrot. (Could people really have confused bright tail-feathers for a bright bill, though??)\r\n\r\nWait, haven\'t we heard this description somewhere before??',0.73125,0.35,45,0,1,1,0,'spotted',0.5916666,0.15,-10,1,144,'bird','Parrot',NULL),(32,'Porkfish','fish/porkfish','Pescetarians are undecided on whether or not it\'s cool to eat this creature.',0.5916666,0.63958,-30,1,0,0,0,'fish',0.26041,0.51041,5,1,35,'fish','Porkfish','A striped fish with a pig nose, pointed ears, and fins that almost look like little arms.'),(33,'Tomate','plant/tomate','\"Knowledge is knowing that a tomate is a fruit; wisdom is not putting it in a fruit salad.\"',0.26875,0.89583333,86,0,0,0,0,'seed',0.54375,0.58125,8,0,133,'plant','Tomate','A sentient tomato; it wears the bit of stem and leaf still attached to its top as if it were hair.\n\nWhere it got its little arms and feetsies from, who knows.'),(34,'Lilzilla','lizard/lilzilla','Until this species was discovered, it was thought that chickens were the closest living relatives to the dinosaurs. As to which is the _cutest_ living relative of the dinosaurs, however, chickens might still have a chance.',0.37,0.845,63,0,0,1,0,'spotted',0.545,0.22,-9,1,35,'lizard','Lilzilla',NULL),(35,'Jelephant','mammal/jelephant','Jelephants are known for their gentle nature and close social bonds. They playfully exchange small tokens, pat noses, and spit at each other to show their affection.',0.75,0.71,15,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.48,0.565,0,1,12,'mammal','Jelephant','A miniature species of elephant. It has a long snout, and short, pointed ears. Like homo sapiens it has a coccyx at the bottom of its spine; a remnant of its tailed ancestors. It owes its name to its hairless, and remarkably-pliable skin.'),(36,'Poppy Dragon','lizard/poppy-dragon','Like the Komodo Dragon, the Poppy Dragon does not breathe fire, or have wings. It _can_ spit streams of water to knock large insects to the ground, though, so I guess it gets a pass?',0.075,0.79,10,0,0,1,0,'speckled-small',0.775,0.725,3,1,35,'lizard','Poppy Dragon',NULL),(37,'Sentinel','cephalopod/sentinel','This telekinetic cephalopod is almost certainly of magical origin.\r\n\r\nBesides the telekinesis, and the eyes on the ends of their tentacles, which are magical enough, Sentinels constantly secrete a pheromone that acts as a deterrent for many would-be predators; even ticks and mosquitoes give them a wide berth.',0.91,0.375,26,1,1,0,1,NULL,0.105,0.005,-123,0,108,'cephalopod','Sentinel',NULL),(38,'Novendecipede','bug/novendecipede','Named for its 19 legs, the Novendecipede carries a poison that can kill up to 20 people in a single bite.\r\n\r\nYeah, 20.\r\n\r\nWith a single bite.\r\n\r\nIt\'s that strong.',0.89,0.735,22,0,0,1,0,'larva',0.78,0.365,-12,1,161,'bug','Novendecipede',NULL),(39,'Grabber','machine/grabber','Yeah, it\'s a robot, but you still need to pet it. Even robots can learn to love.\r\n\r\nAnd to eat and poop, apparently...',0.74,0.21,27,0,0,0,0,'question-block',0.38,0.545,-49,0,188,'machine','Grabber','A metal box for a body; a smaller metal box for a head. It uses its four wheels to get around, and the articulated grabby arm on the top of its head to hold things.'),(40,'Sentient Beetle','bug/sentient-beetle','This beetle was granted sentience via the AWESOME POWER OF SCIENCE.\r\n\r\nScience. Is there anything it _can\'t_ do?',0.865,0.63,12,0,0,0,0,'fish',0.665,0.5,-20,0,188,'bug','Sentient Beetle',NULL),(41,'Hedgehog','mammal/hedgehog','I heard these little guys really like chili dogs? There aren\'t any chili dogs in Poppy Seed Pets, though, so it\'s hard to know for sure.',0,0.95,106,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.805,0.73,7,0,34,'mammal','Hedgehog','A hedgehog. It\'s not going _anywhere_ fast with those little legs, though.'),(42,'Giant Snail','gastropod/just-a-snail','Not all Giant Snails have such vibrant shells. Just the really snazzy ones. (That\'s a scientific _fact_.)',0.815,0.9,61,0,0,0,0,'fish',0.46,0.465,1,1,121,'gastropod','Giant Snail',NULL),(43,'Poire','plant/pear','This hideous creature is the result of a Tarasque mating with a Pear.\r\n\r\n\"That\'s not possible,\" I hear you say.\r\n\r\nYeah.\r\n\r\nThat\'s what we all thought.',0.405,0.865,51,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.585,0.265,0,1,121,'plant','Poire','A pear-shaped creature covered in spots, and possessing a large mouth lined with razor-sharp teeth.\r\n\r\nIt has a little stem & leaf on the top of its head, two little stick arms, and two nubbins for feet; no real legs to speak of.'),(44,'Painter Gecko','lizard/painter-gecko','So-named because of the brush-stroke-like stripes on its body. Or was it the paintbrush-shaped tail?\r\n\r\nOne of those, anyway.',0.79,0.725,32,0,0,0,0,'striped-small',0.675,0.45,-15,1,35,'lizard','Painter Gecko','This lizard runs around on two feet - its only limbs - which are attached to its body by spindly legs.\n\nIt has a thick tail which resembles a voluminous paintbrush brush, and on each side of its head and long, colorful frills that almost look like wings.'),(45,'Wibblet','monotreme/wibblet','In the Hollow Earth, it enjoys warm climates, and eating bugs.\r\n\r\nHere on the surface, it\'s found turning down the thermostat, and _never_ eating bugs!\r\n\r\nWhy this change in behavior?\r\n\r\n\\*shrugs\\*',0.49,0.665,80,0,0,0,0,'spotted',0.52,0.435,2,1,34,'monotreme','Wibblet',NULL),(46,'Ham','mammal/eee-piggie','You know how people are always saying \"when pigs fly\"? Well, pets _can_ wear Wings, so...',0.24,0.76,-58,1,1,0,1,NULL,0.35,0.59,15,1,34,'mammal','Ham',NULL),(47,'Mochabo','bird/mochabo','Though they appear to be biologically capable of making noise, no one has heard the chirp of a Mochabo, giving the impression that this species of flightless bird is either very shy, or very sneaky.\r\n\r\nOh, and they also smell like coffee. So there\'s that.',0.145,0.36,-176,1,0,1,0,'speckled',0.35,0.31,58,1,144,'bird','Mochabo','A large, flightless bird, reminiscent of the emu or ostrich, but with a thicker neck, and shorter wings. The feathers on the back of its head are as long as its tailfeathers. Much more subdued than a peacock, they give an almost elegant, or regal look to the creature.'),(48,'Pvirla','mammal/pvirla','The spots under its eyes are eyespots - false eyes evolved to give the appearance that the Pvirla is alert even while it sleeps, warding off predators.',0.85,0.645,19,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.45,0.415,-8,1,34,'mammal','Pvirla',NULL),(49,'Flaand','slime/flaand','This scaly creature - thought to share a common ancestor with the land slug - reproduces via pseudogamous parthogenesis. It lays its soft-shelled eggs in damp nests, occasionally drooling a nutrient-rich mucous on them.\r\n\r\nYeah. Life is pretty weird, sometimes.',0.205,0.655,9,0,0,0,0,'fish',0.475,0.63,-7,1,35,'slime','Flaand','It\'s shaped like a child\'s drawing of a hand, but a hand with only four fingers... and little legs coming out the bottom of where the wrist would be. A disappointed face sits just above the \"palm\".'),(50,'Alot','mammal/alot','According to Google Trends, within the US the Alot is searched for most in Mississippi. There is no known explanation for this phenomenon; Mississippians just really like the little cuties, I guess.',0.75,0.78,27,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.475,0.475,0,1,34,'mammal','Alot','It has a squarish body topped with two, pointed ears. Perhaps its most distinguishing feature, however, is the bulls-eye-shaped coloration on its stomach. It walks upright on its two legs, which are even shorter than its two small arms.'),(51,'Earthkin','elemental/earthkin','Despite being made of minerals and rock, this creature is surprisingly flexible.\r\n\r\nAnd what luxurious hair!',0.275,0.9,80,0,0,0,0,'rock',0.49,0.45,-1,1,141,'elemental','Earthkin',NULL),(52,'Salad','mammal/salad','Thought to be the result of magical experiments on a Mandelbrat. Why it\'s called \"Salad\", though, is anyone\'s guess...',0.755,0.705,63,0,1,1,1,NULL,0.705,0.41,0,1,34,'mammal','Salad','This dog-like creature is shaped like a yellow squash, or perhaps an eggplant (but way cuter than that vile, vile fruit!) It carries itself on its two, short hind legs - the only limbs it has - aided by its slightly-longer tail, which it uses for balance.'),(53,'Flightless Onion-tail','lizard/flightless-oniontail','It is thought that increased competition in the skies with other dragons led this species of Onion-tail to give up flight, and seek food on the ground. Its softer eggs suggest adaptation to fresh water. Perhaps it adopted a more fish-heavy diet?',0.715,0.355,157,0,0,1,0,'speckled-small',0.635,0.17,7,1,144,'lizard','Flightless Onion-tail','Giraffe-shaped, with medium-long legs and neck, pointed ossicones, and, of course, the distinctive, brightly-colored bulb just above its butt.'),(54,'Dapper Swan','bird/dapper-swan','This species of swan gets its name for its colorful markings, which resemble a necktie.\r\n\r\nAlso of note: it hovers.',0.785,0.38,43,0,1,1,0,'striped',0.59,0.17,2,1,144,'bird','Dapper Swan','Like a bird, the Dapper Swan has a beak, but it otherwise bears a closer resemblance to a snake, having a long, slender body, and no feet, wings, or limbs or any kind.\r\n\r\nIt moves by some unknown power, hovering inches off the ground.'),(55,'Fog Elemental','elemental/fog','Clouds come in all kinds of shapes: Bunnies... Desikhs... professional wrestlers doing spinning headlock elbow drops...\r\n\r\nSo why does this one just look like some kinda\'... sky poopy?',0.585,0.385,56,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.45,0.095,-16,1,301,'elemental','Fog Elemental',NULL),(56,'Lily of the Sea','plant/lily-of-the-sea','Related to the Lily of the Valley, this plant creates extensive colonies by extending its roots outward. Unlike the Lily of the Valley, the colonies this plant creates float, carried by ocean currents.\r\n\r\nAlso, its flowers are sentient.',0.6,0.765,-77,1,0,1,1,NULL,0.575,0.425,19,1,356,'plant','Lily of the Sea','Its body is a tulip-like flower turned upside-down; long legs poke out from beneath its petals, barely visible. The stem on the top of its head varies in length across individuals, depending on where exactly they broke off from their mother plant.'),(57,'Possum Drop','mammal/possumdrop','If at all possible, try not to stand directly beneath a member of this invasive species.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, they\'re as sneaky as they are prolific, so it\'s basically impossible _not_ to stand directly beneath one at least once a day.',0.445,0.15,-55,0,1,1,1,NULL,0.85,0.07,-12,1,34,'mammal','Possum Drop',NULL),(58,'Parapet Mushroom','fungus/square','Named for the fortifications of castles under which this fungus can often be found.',0.955,0.76,38,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.475,0.215,-3,1,39,'fungus','Parapet Mushroom','A large, spongy cube. Its wide face is positioned high on its body, while its short arms are low. Its skin is two-toned, creating an upside-down \"V\" shape starting at a point on its belly, and extending down to include its short, wide-set legs.'),(59,'Merdragon','fish/wibbly','\"Half merman, half dragon.\"\r\n\r\nIt sounded so good, on paper.',0.335,0.685,-38,0,1,0,0,'fish',0.795,0.29,0,1,35,'fish','Merdragon',NULL),(60,'Shrublin','plant/shrub','I mean. It\'s a sentient shrub. There\'s not much to say.',0.545,0.62,22,0,1,0,1,NULL,0.495,0.695,-9,1,3,'plant','Shrublin',NULL),(61,'◻◻◻◻','elemental/tig\'s','◼◼◼ ◼ ◼◼◼◼◼◼ ◼◼◼ ◼◼◼◼.\r\n\r\n◼◼ ◼◼◼◼◼ ◼ ◼.\r\n\r\n◼◼◼◼◼◼◼◼◼ ◼◼ ◼◼◼.',0.36,0.625,-43,1,0,0,1,NULL,0.57,0.06,-19,1,10,'elemental','Lost',NULL),(62,'Nanerbird','bird/naner','Named for its diet (primarily Naners, and other tropical fruits), but known primarily for its very-luscious (and very un-bird-like) lips.\r\n\r\nIt might have been known for its kite-like tail, but those lips! Just... whoa. Nature. Dang. But I mean, you know: you do you; who am _I_ to argue with millions of years of evolution.',0.645,0.735,87,0,1,0,0,'speckled',0.655,0.33,0,1,144,'bird','Nanerbird',NULL),(63,'Yyrn','cephalopod/yyrn','A creature from the Deep Umbra that was tamed after generations of regimented breeding, and a strict, Beans-based diet.',0.595,0.705,49,0,0,1,0,'fish',0.49,0.1,-5,1,35,'cephalopod','Yyrn',NULL),(64,'Pipe Rat','mammal/pipe-rat','These rodents, native to lakes and rivers, are able to hold their breath for up to 15 minutes. They burrow just under the muddy bed of their home waters, and lie in wait for fish, frogs, and small water snakes, surfacing only for the occasional breath of air.\r\n\r\nIn river cities, they\'re often found in leaf-filled rain gutters with small litters. It\'s thought that urban environments provides easy food for the parents, in the form of human waste, giving them more time to care for and protect their young.\r\n\r\nAdorable.',0.435,0.635,-48,1,0,1,1,NULL,0.415,0.325,12,1,34,'mammal','Pipe Rat',NULL),(65,'Gelp','lizard/gelp','This tiny, bumpy lizard has a disproportionately-large maw, which it uses to swallow most of its food whole.\r\n\r\nThere\'s one story of a pet-owner who got a Gelp as a playmate for their new kitten, only to watch the Gelp swallow the kitten in one, swift motion. So if you\'re looking for an unusual playmate for _your_ kitten, maybe just get a ferret, instead.',0.895,0.725,77,0,0,1,0,'speckled-small',0.665,0.505,0,1,35,'lizard','Gelp',NULL),(66,'Upo','mammal/upo','It\'s unclear where the name \"Upo\" comes from, however there is a gourd - not entirely dissimilar in shape - known in the Philippines as \"úpo\", so maybe that\'s it?\r\n\r\nOr maybe the name was once an acronym for \"unidentified pig object,\" but that seems somehow less plausible. (I mean, I get the curly tail, but look at those _ears_!)',0.145,0.735,-31,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.495,0.395,0,1,34,'mammal','Upo',NULL),(67,'Rho','lizard/rho','Not many creatures have five legs.\r\n\r\nBut some do.\r\n\r\nNot many creatures have fat tails with sticky pads on the end.\r\n\r\nBut this one do.',0.37,0.515,44,0,0,1,0,'spotted',0.67,0.67,0,1,35,'lizard','Rho',NULL),(68,'Pobo','spirit/bone','The remains of some unknown creature became possessed by the spirit of some unknown creature. Are the remains and the spirit from the _same_ creature? The odds seem low, but it\'d nice if it were true.',0.33,0.635,-51,1,0,0,1,NULL,0.485,0.235,0,0,108,'spirit','Pobo','A single bone held aloft by a wisp of ethereal ghostness.'),(69,'Diaboru','mammal/diaboru','Don\'t be fooled by the Diaboru\'s innocent appearance: it will devour you whole in an instant if you so much as begin to turn your back on it!\r\n\r\nNah, I\'m just kidding: these things\'re 100% darling!',0.75,0.735,43,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.52,0.36,0,1,87,'mammal','Diaboru','The Diaboru has an almost perfectly-spherical body, a pair of antlers, and four, stubby legs that may or may not have hooves at their ends.\r\n\r\nIt\'s hard to tell from the picture.\r\n'),(70,'Noucan','bird/noucan','This misshapen bird is capable of mimicking human speech, but only seems interested in making the occasional contrary statement.',0.29,0.745,78,0,0,1,0,'speckled-small',0.475,0.445,-18,1,144,'bird','Noucan','Bear with me for a sec; this one is weird to describe. Take a squat \"J\", and rotate it 180 degrees... what was the tail of the \"J\" is the Noucan\'s bill, which curves downwards. Its long face curves seamlessly into its body, which has stick arms instead of wings, and is completed with equally stick-ish legs. The top of its head has three feathers that stick up and out from the rest. Finally - and this is the most-important part - I _guarantee_ that if you try to draw what I just described, it\'s gonna come out totally different from what I\'m looking at.'),(71,'Tufted Screamer','lizard/screamer','There\'s not much that can be said about this creature, if for no other reason than that it\'s almost impossible to say _anything_ when it decides to scream. But real quick, before it starts up, you might be surprised to learn that the Tufted Screamer is a type of Iguana, and probably _won\'t_ be surprised to learn that the \"tuft\" on its head is just some sticky-uppy scales, and not a tuft of hair.',0.76,0.62,-12,0,1,0,0,'striped',0.475,0.45,-22,1,35,'lizard','Tufted Screamer','A round, almost-spherical creature whose entire body is taken up by its mouth, and two, beady eyes.\r\n\r\nThe length of its tongue seems to exceed the diameter of its body.\r\n\r\nAnd somehow all of this is supported and carried by two tiny, stick legs.'),(72,'Dwarf Sky Whale','mammal/whale','The sky in the center of the Hollow Earth is host to an entire ecosystem, including several species of whale. One of the most populous species - and the only one suitable to keep as a pet - is the Dwarf Sky Whale.\n\nDespite having no wings, and a single, small tailfin, it\'s somehow able to lift its body upwards. It only manages a low hover here, but in the Hollow Earth it soars.',0.16,0.425,31,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.735,0.42,13,1,34,'mammal','Dwarf Sky Whale',NULL),(73,'Phoenix','bird/phoenix','They say a Phoenix can never die. But _none_ of the pets die in Poppy Seed Pets, so... you know... eh.',0.15,0.28,-26,1,0,0,0,'spotted',0.585,0.345,10,0,353,'bird','Phoenix',NULL),(74,'Mïp','mammal/miip','Named for the noise it makes: a distinctive \"mïp-a-_chu!_\"\r\n\r\nIf anything about this this reminds you of another pet-based game, that\'s purely a coincidence. I mean, for starters, the Mïp is of the genus Canis; not of Ochotona, as is the mascot creature of some _other_, totally-hypothetical video game series you _might_ be conjuring up in your imagination.',0.045,0.9,116,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.49,0.515,2,1,34,'mammal','Mïp','A sphere with two tiny legs, and two pointed ears. Its eyes are set far apart on its body. The fur on the top of its head has a striped pattern, which helps it camouflage in the dry bushes of its native territory.'),(75,'Glyryvyru','elemental/glyryvyru','Myths speak of the Glyryvillu, an ancient creature that dwells in lakes. Some describe it as a serpent with the head of a fox; others say it\'s a flat, circular creature with eyes around the edge of its body.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, while myths have almost nothing to say about the Glyryvyru, we know _exactly_ what it looks like: ADORABLE!',0.375,0.75,82,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.475,0.36,-15,1,94,'elemental','Glyryvyru','It stands upright, looking like a squat little goblin, with short, pointed ears, and long, floppy arms. Its mouth is hidden behind a long, striped, hairless snout that reveals the Glyryvyru\'s colorful skin.'),(76,'Wiy','slime/wiy','DNA testing by expert scientists has revealed that the Wiy doesn\'t _have_ any DNA. Taste testing by expert chefs, on the other hand, has revealed that the bulk of the Wiy\'s mass is corn starch.\r\n\r\nThe most-widely accepted theory among expert wizards is that the Wiy was the result of an ancient aleuromagical ritual gone awry.\r\n\r\nMeanwhile, experts in the field of education point to the Wiy as an example of the value of cross-disciplinary studies.\r\n\r\nAnd as for me? Well, I\'m no expert, but I\'m willing to put my faith in those who are.',0.675,0.685,58,0,1,1,1,NULL,0.5,0.46,0,1,25,'slime','Wiy',NULL),(77,'Sága Jelling','scyphozoa/jelling','',0.22,0.655,-43,1,0,0,0,'polyp',0.315,0.56,20,0,683,'scyphozoa','Sága Jelling',NULL),(78,'ML-52β','lizard/missing-link','Missing Link 52β was first proposed by biologist Kip Garnier, as an alternative to his brother Theo Garnier\'s Missing Link 52, with which Kip saw several issues.\r\n\r\nKip\'s theory was proven right when this species was discovered in February 2022 by HERG\'s head researcher Dr. Eve Heidel.\r\n\r\nThe full repercussions of this discovery are still being debated.',0.085,0.585,38,0,0,0,0,'speckled',0.625,0.57,-15,1,35,'lizard','Missing Link','A walking fish, it has six, short legs, a split tail, a long, bony crest on its head, and a short beak.'),(79,'Pogger','monotreme/pogger','On [the Everyone Makes Stuff discord server](https://discord.gg/xQ4Fh4NEYZ), players noted this creature\'s resemblance to the platypus, and suggested names accordingly.\r\n\r\nPussyplat. Pussplaty.\r\n\r\nThough many player suggestions are quite good, these particular suggestions were ignored.',0.75,0.65,34,0,0,1,0,'spotted',0.485,0.29,-3,1,34,'monotreme','Pogger',NULL),(80,'Handhat','slime/handhat','This creature seems more like the kind of thing you\'d see as an enemy in a video game.\r\n\r\nNOT _THIS_ VIDEO GAME!',0.855,0.535,44,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.495,0.655,3,1,27,'slime','Handhat','A slime blop with a single arm extending from its top. It has piercing eyes that are visible even in the darkest environments.'),(81,'Walking Angler','lizard/walking-angler','This amphibious angler has lost its predatory nature, and walks around in fascination of its own lure. What evolutionary advantage this provides is still unknown.\r\n\r\nThen again, maybe there is none. Maybe a wizard did it.\r\n\r\nUgh. Wizards. Always makin\' science difficult.',0.73,0.715,15,0,0,0,0,'striped-small',0.42,0.455,-36,1,35,'lizard','Walking Angler',NULL),(82,'Giant Bee','bug/bee','It\'s a straight-up bee, y\'all!',0.535,0.595,-78,1,0,0,0,'larva',0.48,0.305,7,0,87,'bug','Giant Bee',NULL),(83,'Ursine','monotreme/ursine','These bear-like animals are most commonly found in forests, but reports of sightings in other places are not uncommon. The Ursine is known for its elusive nature, appearing and disappearing mysteriously.\n\nCombined with a fur that shimmers in the light, and ears that often move independently, the Ursine sometimes gives off an otherworldly vibe, despite being universally considered cute.',0.805,0.535,5,0,0,1,0,'speckled',0.43,0.275,-14,1,34,'monotreme','Ursine','Eeeeeeeeee!! It\'s like a cute little teddy bear!'),(84,'Star-eyed Tiger Discus','fish/star-eyed-tiger-discus','How does this species of fish survive in your house, outside of the water, for so long? I guess that\'s the \"tiger\" part.',0.415,0.625,-25,1,0,1,0,'fish',0.53,0.29,9,1,35,'fish','Star-eyed Tiger Discus','A large, flat fish with stripes running across its body, and fins that extend from its head, all the way back to its short tail.'),(85,'Infinity Imp','elemental/infinity-imp','An abstract entity from the imaginary plane. It was thought that they could never exist in our world, but the creatures from the other side of the portal - Poppy Seed Pets - are inexplicably capable of pulling Infinity Imps into reality.',0.7,0.815,29,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.505,0.29,0,0,713,'elemental','Infinity Imp','A plump creature with a cat-like face, and large, golden eyes. In addition to its two arms and two legs, the Infinity Imp has two wings which, though physically detached, are nonetheless part of its body.'),(86,'Tortle','lizard/turtle','This species of turtle has a prehensile tail, which is convenient for the developer of Poppy Seed Pets to use as the place to put held items-- er, I mean, which is convenient for holding, you know, like, swords \'n\' stuff.',0.04,0.715,29,0,0,1,0,'speckled',0.83,0.59,-20,1,35,'lizard','Tortle','A turtle with hexagonal-shaped plates across the top of its shell, and rows of spots around the shell\'s outer edges.'),(87,'Flour Wisp','elemental/flour-wisp','An ancient spirit of cooking, coated with a thin layer of flour, and said to know every recipe ever learned, and every recipe yet to be discovered.\n\nIf only it could speak.',0.685,0.68,46,0,1,1,1,NULL,0.415,0.415,-24,1,16,'elemental','Flour Wisp','A round critter with two nubbins for legs, four insect-like wings, and a colorful bauble on its head.'),(88,'Fork-tongued Rizald','lizard/fork-tongued-rizald','The classification of this species is a source of controversy among biologists. Rizalds have several mammalian features which make categorizing it a \"reptile\" questionable. However, as a (mostly) scaly, egg-laying creature with no mammary glands, \"mammal\" was felt to be less correct than the other available options, and so Rizalds - including the Fork-tongued Rizald - are currently (and by some, begrudgingly) classified as reptiles.',0.88,0.49,49,0,0,1,0,'spotted',0.65,0.265,-15,1,35,'lizard','Fork-tongued Rizald','It has a long, spotted, snake-like body, a prehensile forked tongue, piercing black eyes, and two large, fluffy rabbit ears.'),(89,'Cooking Buddy','machine/cooking-buddy','The inventors of the Cooking Buddy never intended it to be capable of sentience...\r\n\r\n... oh well!',0.72,0.55,36,0,1,0,0,'egg-timer',0.485,0.42,0,0,195,'machine','Cooking Buddy','An egg-shaped friend with a low-res LCD display for rendering its eyes.'),(90,'Pebble','mammal/pebble','If you ever doubted that Poppy Seed Pets may be of alien origin, consider the Pebble. Not even the most disturbing creature of the deep sea has the Pebble beat in terms of sheer, visual absurdity! Which makes sense, really, given the Pebble\'s uncanny resemblance to one of Earth\'s weirdest-looking land-dwelling creatures: the pug.',0.5,0.725,58,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.5,0.415,0,1,34,'mammal','Pebble','It looks like a pug face with two little legs. Possibly because that\'s exactly what it is.'),(91,'Kejoro','spirit/totally-hair','This creature is named after the Japanese Kejōrō, a yokai that appears as a young woman whose face and body is completely obscured by long hair.\r\n\r\nFortunately, that\'s where the similarities end: _this_ spirit will _not_ slice you to pieces with its hair should you approach it! Quite the contrary: it loves to be pet!',0.315,0.48,116,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.495,0.08,-10,0,34,'spirit','Kejoro','An elongated mass of unkempt hair... which it can apparently use to hold things, so that\'s neat.'),(92,'Gobbun','lizard/gobbun','This subspecies of goblin is unusual from others in three major aspects:\r\n\r\n1. It is unusually docile.\r\n2. It has a \"gold earring\" - a yellow piece of skin on one ear - that appears to play a part in mate-selection.\r\n3. Each foot has two toes with very thick toenails; when it walks, it walks on the heels of its feet, but when it runs, it runs on its toes as if they were hooves.\r\n\r\nThese differences set it so far apart from other goblin subspecies, magical intervention is suspected... but for what purpose?',0.495,0.76,60,0,0,1,0,'spotted',0.455,0.23,-8,1,35,'lizard','Gobbun','A squart creature that walks upright on two legs. It has a large head that sports medium-length pointed ears, one bearing its signature \"earring\". It has a short and thick pointed tail, and two stick-thin arms. Its belly is a different color from the rest of its body.'),(93,'Pricklepounce','mammal/pricklepounce','Native to arid regions of the Hollow Earth, the Pricklepounce is an ambush predator. It waits in dry bushes for smaller mammals to come by in search of shade, then strikes them with its barbed tail.',0.815,0.71,41,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.675,0.335,-10,1,34,'mammal','Pricklepounce','A cat-like creature with a striped tail that ends with a vicious-looking barb. It fur has a distinctive, splotchy, tri-color pattern.'),(94,'Leaf Dove','bird/leaf-dove','The leaf dove is capable of holding its breath for almost half an hour! It uses this ability to remain completely motionless, so as not to startle its prey: leaf-eating insects. Lured in by it\'s leaf-like appendage, locusts and other insects approach the Leaf Dove for a meal, only to become one, themselves!\r\n\r\nA sneaky hunter; and a cute one!',0.325,0.79,60,0,0,1,0,'speckled-small',0.485,0.5,0,1,144,'bird','Leaf Dove','A pear-shaped bird with puffy cheeks, and a leaf-like appendage on its head. It also sports four wings: a pair of full, extravagant wings, and a pair of smaller ones, which do not aid in flight, and are instead used to hold on to things.'),(95,'Bear Frog','monotreme/bear-frog','This fuzzy monotreme sports bear-shaped ears, and a leathery, spotted rump. It lays soft eggs in lakes, usually the same lake it was born in.\r\n\r\nBear Frogs are primarily nocturnal, hunting and calling for mates under the cover of darkness.',0.56,0.62,72,0,0,1,1,'fish',0.495,0.465,0,1,34,'monotreme','Bear Frog',NULL),(96,'Red Piper','bird/red-piper','Named for the red plumage on its neck, this bird spends most of its life in water, fishing for insects, tadpoles, and other, smaller critters that can be found in and on the water.',0.78,0.41,26,0,0,1,0,'striped-small',0.53,0.3,-14,1,144,'bird','Red Piper','A small bird with an elegant crest, and bright red neck plumage. It has long legs ending in webbed feet, which it uses to paddle around in the water, and a pointed beak which it uses for fishing.'),(97,'Miocene Azawakh','mammal/miocene-azawakh','This dog is believed to be an ancestor of modern-day Azawakhs. It shares their muscular build and long legs. Unlike modern Azawakhs, it has long, pointed ears, which it keeps upright unless hiding, or scared.',1,0.795,-90,0,1,1,1,NULL,0.645,0.22,-4,1,34,'mammal','Miocene Azawakh',NULL),(98,'Catacomb Spirit','spirit/cat-ghost','This friendly spirit is found in catacombs, where it spends the majority of its time sleeping amidst the bones.',0.29,0.52,-31,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.58,0.265,-5,0,108,'spirit','Catacomb Spirit','A long spirit with cat ears and a tapered body devoid of limbs. It has blush marks under its eyes, and is surrounded by motes of magic.'),(99,'Long-nose Jerboa','mammal/longnose-jerboa','When cactus flowers are in bloom, this spotted species of Jerboa uses its long nose to drink their nectar. It drinks as much as it can before hibernating until the next flowering season.',0.775,0.655,68,0,0,0,1,NULL,0.775,0.655,0,1,34,'mammal','Long-nose Jerboa','A round, spotted, mouse-like creature with a long nose and a hairy tuft on the end of its tail.'),(100,'Duster-tailed Fox','mammal/duster-tail-fox','The Hollow Earth is littered with abandoned towns. Those found in the desert have since become popular breeding-grounds for Duster-tailed Foxes. The shade offered by the buildings attracts many creatures, which these foxes hunt.',0.76,0.69,36,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.62,0.285,0,1,34,'mammal','Duster-tailed Fox','Their fur is a solid color, except for their hands, giving the appearance of wearing gloves. They have wide, but short, broom-shaped tails.'),(101,'Quirl','mammal/squirrel','In many ways, this species resembles the common squirrel. Their DNA is such a close match, that they cannot have diverged very long ago, suggesting that squirrels have traveled to the Hollow Earth relatively recently. (You know: on geological timescales, and all that.)',0.205,0.33,34,0,1,1,1,NULL,0.755,0.47,-5,1,34,'mammal','Quirl','It walks on all fours, and has a long, fuzzy tail. A dark stripe runs along the length of its back. Between its rounded ears is a little tuft of red hair.'),(102,'The Bones','monotreme/the-bones','',0.61,0.6,61,0,0,1,0,'plain',0.515,0.15,0,1,87,'monotreme','The Bones','A large, round creature with two large, curved teeth, like a walrus\'s, and two pointed ears... unless maybe they\'re horns? It\'s hard to say.\n\nIt has no arms, but its two large, flat feet make it an excellent swimmer.'),(103,'Grar','mammal/grar','A strange, lumpy creature whose almost-entire body is dedicated to its mouth... stranger still, perhaps, is that this is not the only creature from the Hollow Earth that could be described this way...\r\n\r\nIt has no arms, no visible ears, and two of the tiniest feet imaginable for a creature of its size.\r\n\r\nBiologists have so far been able to determine how evolution produced such a creature, unless... ugh: do you think it was wizards?\r\n\r\n_Again?_\r\n\r\nFrickin\' wizards.',0.71,0.57,51,0,0,1,1,NULL,0.42,0.25,-19,1,34,'mammal','Grar','A large blob of a creature with a large toothy smile, two small eyes, two small feet, and that\'s about it!'),(104,'False Frog','amphibian/false-frog','I mean, think about it: a real frog couldn\'t possibly be _this_ cute! So, you know, _scientifically speaking_, this has gotta\' be some kinda\' _false_ frog!',0.455,0.685,72,0,0,1,0,'fish',0.555,0.29,-6,1,95,'amphibian','False Frog','A rotund creature with a wide mouth, and large eyes. Its underbelly is a different color from the rest of its body. It has webbed hands and feet, and its arms are longer than its legs. (Which is maybe also a clue this thing is not a true frog: the little guy _cannot_ jump to save its life.)'),(105,'Cloud Seal','amphibian/cloud-seal','The Cloud Seal is not a mammal, as its name suggests, but an amphibian that swims through clouds as easily as it does fresh water.\n\nWhen it\'s time to spawn, many females gather together to lay eggs in the same river bed, and share the responsibility of watching over them from the sky. Their hawk-like vision allows them to spot potential predators from a great distance, an ability they also use to hunt.\n\nWhen their offspring begin to emerge as tadpoles, the mothers drop food in from above, then leave them to their fate, in search of new mates. The food they leave behind is enough to last the tadpoles until they can crawl onto land and begin hunting on their own, starting with small insects and bugs.',0.7,0.735,131,0,1,1,0,'fish',0.615,0.47,-12,1,1262,'amphibian','Cloud Seal','A long, leathery creature with two fore-flippers, and a wide tail. Its face is doggish, like a seal\'s. Its underbelly is a different color from the rest of its body.'),(106,'Binauris Frutex','plant/binauris-frutex','Perhaps the most-surprising thing about this plant species is that it evolved ears that function similarly to that of a mammal\'s, but instead of two small bones in its middle ear, Binauris Frutex uses stiff stems.\r\n\r\nBananas!',0.535,0.7,39,0,0,1,0,'seed',0.515,0.49,3,1,42,'plant','Binauris Frutex','A lump of a shrub, with two, wide-set feet. It has a thorny mouth, but its most distinguishing feature is the two leaves that stand out from either side of its head, and serve as ears.'),(107,'Cat-- er... pillar?','bug/notcat','This species of tiny cat has-- er, wait a minute: that\'s not a tiny cat! It\'s some kind of cute & fuzzy cater<em>pillar</em>?!',0.915,0.58,-20,1,1,1,0,'striped-small',0.445,0.35,0,1,34,'bug','Cat-- er... pillar?','Its body is made of five, fuzzy segments of alternating colors. One of those segments bears its face, with two, large, deep-black eyes, and tufts that look like puffy, fuzzy cheeks.'),(108,'Majestosa','lizard/majestosa','When first cataloged by a team of HERG scientists, the creature was to be named \"Winged Paradise\", however one member of the team was convinced the animal looked familiar, and after a couple days of searching realized why: a sketch of it appears in the notes of Portuguese explorer Estêvão de Noronha Almeida during one of his expeditions in 1528. He described the creature as being a majestic one - \"uma ciatura majestosa\" - which ultimately lead the team to settle on the name \"Majestosa\" for this species.',0.535,0.74,-124,1,1,1,0,'speckled-small',0.095,0.61,-38,1,35,'lizard','Majestosa','A long, thin, flying snake. It has two white wings that are flecked with color.'),(109,'Arnoldson\'s Chlamydosaurus','lizard/arnoldsons-chlamydosaurus','Named after its discoverer, field researcher Fisk Arnoldson. It is the second known species of the genus Chlamydosaurus.',0.645,0.825,45,0,0,0,0,'striped-small',0.54,0.435,-4,1,35,'lizard','Arnoldson\'s Chlamydosaurus','A frill-necked lizard with thick stripes on its back. It walks upright.'),(110,'Gooplin','slime/gooplin','The EFSA and FDA are still reviewing the Gooplin\'s suitability for human consumption.\r\n\r\nPlease don\'t eat your Gooplin.\r\n\r\nYet.',0.415,0.7,-46,0,1,1,1,NULL,0.47,0.34,0,1,29,'slime','Gooplin','A large, bell-shaped, semi-translucent slime.'),(111,'Dancing Sword','elemental/sword','A sword brought to life.\r\n\r\nSeems a little dangerous to keep as a pet, but... you do you, I guess.',0.7,0.875,41,0,0,0,-1,NULL,0.5,0.41,-47,0,36,'elemental','Dancing Sword','A basic sword with two legs, but no arms, and no discernible face! (How does this thing even work?? I guess that\'s just the power of the Philosopher\'s Stone...)');
/*!40000 ALTER TABLE `pet_species` ENABLE KEYS */;
